[Event "Masterful Moves: Gukesh"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "What is in this course"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]

{ This is not a normal tactics course!And thatâs a good thing. There are plenty of tactics courses available here already. This course provides a special selection of content and puzzles. It challenges you in different ways and understanding them will help you get the most out of it: The puzzles are all from real games of one player Just like in a real game you will not know what sort of tactic or sequence you are looking for and just like in a real game more than one move might be plausible. Some tactics are short - two or three moves long - whereas others may require a longer sequence of moves to reach a conclusion. The puzzles are a mix of tactical and positional There are, for example, some simple checkmates from his days as a junior starting out in tournament chess; there are sharp tactical lines from online and over the board master-level play; and there are positional ideas such as an exchange sacrifice to reach a better endgame. Youâll find all of these and more in this course. The puzzles are grouped by year And thatâs because we are following Gukeshâs journey to the top of world chess. Together, we will see how he develops from his early days playing in junior events right through to his attaining the Grandmaster title and on to the World Championship match. Each chapter covers one calendar year except for the first one which brings together Gukeshâs earliest days as a player from 2013-2016. Each puzzle has a difficulty rating This helps you know what to expect. There is a wide range of difficulty in the puzzles. One star is the simplest, all the way up to five stars which denotes the hardest puzzles to solve. There are key Guki-Style-Factors to look out for Some ideas are seen in many of Gukeshâs tactics â look out for clever ways to activate the queen or to utilise pins by rooks or bishops to limit the opponent's movement, for example. We highlight these factors in chapter one of the course and mention them in the annotations to the games. The full moves of each game are included You are challenged to solve a tactical or positional sequence from the game but once you have done so you can review how Gukesh set up the possibility in the first place. Gukesh uses a number of strategic themes to build a position where tactics are possible. He loves to advance the pawns in front of his king, for instance. Weâll point out these themes to you throughout the course so that you get to know them quickly and can start using them in your own games. Youâll also come to appreciate Gukeshâs style and will enjoy his games â including in the World Championship â all the more. Details of tournaments and biographical information about the players are included Gukesh played in a large number of tournaments around the world as he rose up the rankings. We detail how he fared in those tournaments and what bearing they had on his quest for norms, FIDE Circuit points and more. We also explain the off the board factors that have contributed to Gukeshâs success. If youâve ever looked at the names of the players next to a puzzle and wondered âwho are they?â then wonder no more. Weâve researched the players Gukesh defeated with his tactics and provide you with background information on them. Look out for 76-year-old Rani Hamid from Bangladesh sheâs now 80 and still a force to be reckoned with at the Olympiad! } 
