[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]

{ Getting the most from this courseBecause this is not a normal tactics course, here we provide some tips and ideas on how to use it to get the most from it. In particular, it's worth noting that different readers can approach this course in different ways. This course details Gukeshâs journey from junior prodigy all the way to the 2024 World Championship There is an Informational at the start of each chapter detailing the key tournaments he played in and landmarks he achieved, along with his FIDE rating at the start and end of each year. It is followed by a 'More about Gukesh' section where you can learn about his background such as his coaches, role models and his approach to the mental side of tournament chess. If you want to learn more about this remarkable young man and his rise to the upper echelons of the world elite, do take time to read these sections in each chapter. As you solve the puzzles in the same chapter as the Informational you have just read, you will see which event each game was from and what contribution it made to Gukeshâs tournament performance. You will also learn about his opponents - some of them crop up in more than one chapter, so do look out for them. Some of the puzzles are tough... We wouldn't expect our solvers to get every puzzle right first time, particularly the four and five-star ones. Many of them are from Grandmaster versus Grandmaster games. This is high level chess, but even Grandmasters make mistakes, and some of the puzzles are particularly hard to get right first time. ...so: You can try to solve the puzzles, or you can play through the games first and read the annotations before having a go at solving them. By studying the positions Gukesh reaches, you can build up familiarity with the possibilities created and revisit the sequences to test yourself again. The spaced repetition feature here is perfect for this. As with any course here, you can set the puzzle timer to suit your preference so if you want more, or less, time to solve then you can control that. We have set the default time for 240 seconds based on feedback from our beta-testers. Some of the lines are long... One thing we noticed about Gukeshâs ability to calculate is that he often finds the top engine move again and again in a long tactical line, and you will be challenged to do the same. Itâs really exciting when you manage to do it, but you donât have to reach that Super-Grandmaster level on your first try. Also, in certain positions, particularly the ones with longer lines, there will be more than one good move because these positions are taken from real games. ...so: Other good moves are set as alternative moves so that you donât get a fail for no reason, and annotations to explain the most notable and instructive alternatives are provided. On the rare occasion when Gukesh does not play the engineâs top choice but still plays a winning line, the top move will be an alternative while you pursue the moves Gukesh played. This course shows you aspects of Gukeshâs style... A special feature of this course are what we call the Guki-Style-Factors. These are the ways he builds up a position to create a tactic such as advancing the pawns in front of his castled king or a feature of the tactical execution itself such as a pin or an exchange sacrifice. We have grouped them under six headings: Advanced pawns - Gukesh loves to get his pawns up the board, even the ones in front of his castled king. Activity - you will learn how he activates his queen with devastating effect and how he uses the whole board, sometimes putting his pieces on surprising squares. Restriction - limiting his opponent's moves and options, particularly restricting their king, is a Gukesh speciality. Sacrifices - giving up material to target the opposing king or to reach a better endgame is an exciting way to play, and you'll learn from how Gukesh does it. Co-ordination - seeing how he uses pieces together to outmanoeuvre or overwhelm the opponent is very instructive. Complexity - Gukesh loves how complex chess is, and he welcomes complicated positions where he feels he can calculate better. The point is that you will see these factors occur and combine throughout this course as you solve the puzzles. Spotting them makes the experience of using this course more enjoyable and our intention is that it will raise your appreciation of how Gukesh wins so many of his games and encourage you to find similar motifs and opportunities in your own games. We have explained the Guki-Style-Factors in a special Informational called Gukesh's style: what to look out for which you will find in the first chapter where we also provide greater detail about them and we link directly to multiple examples within the course. It is, naturally, up to you how and when you use this information. ...so you could: I Solve the puzzles and build up your own ideas about Gukeshâs style before comparing with our findings. High-level players in particular may take this route. II Read the summary in chapter one, solve the puzzles while looking out for examples along the way and then use the further detail in chapter one as a handy reference and conclusion to heighten your enjoyment of Gukesh's games. III Read the summary and all the detail in chapter one first before solving the puzzles. The video content in chapter one provides even more information. While high-level players might find this method reveals too much for their liking, other players will benefit from this preparatory reading and watching before diving into the puzzles and may find it a richer and more rewarding experience to have perused this extra guidance and the video content first. Weâre here to help You can post questions, queries and feedback in the course forum and in the comments within any puzzle. We read all the feedback and will reply and help out wherever we can. In the video that accompanies this section we explain even more about how to use this course, our appreciation of Gukesh's style and successes and what we have learned while compiling this course, so do check that out too! } 
1.--   *


