[Event "Masterful Moves: Gukesh"]
[White "1) Gukesh's style"]
[Black "Introduction - Gukesh's style: what to look out for"]
[Result "0-1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]

{ Guki-Style-FactorsAs we played through Gukesh's games to select interesting tactical sequences we were also looking at his style of play and how he likes to set up his position. We have grouped our favourite observations into Guki-Style-Factors GSFs, that apply to individual pieces and also to how his pieces work together. Some themes involve how he sets up the tactic - advancing a pawn or pawns far up the board, for example - whereas others are part of the tactical sequence itself - such as pins or Zwischenzugs. Knowing that Gukesh is an AlphaZero fan, we have also looked out for where he uses AlphaZero style motifs in his play. In this informational we introduce each Guki-Style-Factor and then see some of these ideas combining to good effect in a game played by Gukesh in 2019 as he builds up and executes his combination. The moves will be shown in the diagram as you play through the game. In the other sections of this Gukesh Style chapter, we will describe and link to examples from the course that demonstrate each of these themes. For example, in the Queen Activity section we describe several ways Gukesh sets about activating his queen, and also the results of it becoming active. Later in the course we will highlight characteristic Gukesh play in the solutions to the puzzles. When you are solving the puzzles in this course, and when you watch Gukesh play, you may find it fun to look out for the Guki-Style-Factors listed below. You can use this chapter to study your favourite styles before you try them out in your own games. Guki-Style-Factors1. Advanced Pawns Far advanced pawns - Gukesh likes to get a pawn or two as far up the board as possible to create tactical possibilities. The pawns might threaten to promote or help with a checkmating attack. Then more specifically... Advancing pawns in front of his castled king - if Gukesh feels that his pawns could be used to gain space or target the enemy king then he will push them as far as he can. Gukesh is comfortable leaving his king with open space around it if he has calculated that the opposing forces cannot get to it quickly enough to do damage. You will see Gukesh's king sometimes standing on its own, devoid of pawn protection with few, if any, of its fellow pieces in the vicinity. And even more specifically... The march of the h-pawn - An AlphaZero theme, Gukesh frequently advances his h-pawn to soften up to opponent's kingside. He had adopted this into his game in 2019 very soon after Game Changer was published, as we will see below. 2. Activity Active queen - Gukesh likes to activate his queen to create tactical threats. We see him putting a high priority on queen activity. Use of the whole board - Gukesh is a wizard at creating open lines for his long range pieces and bringing his shorter range pieces - knights and pawns - right into the action. This section is about his use of the whole board - the centre and the edges - sides and corners - to maximise his power and impact on key lines and squares. 3. Restriction With his coach GM Prassana, Gukesh studied the games of Magnus Carlsen to see how the former World Champion gradually overwhelmed his opponents by restricting their position until they were squeezed into submission. The opposing king is restricted - Gukesh frequently plays to restrict the opponent's king and then targets it once immobile. This is also an AlphaZero theme, although we do also have plenty of examples of Gukesh targeting a restricted king even before AlphaZero. Pins - Consistent with his strategy of getting open lines and active pieces for himself, while keeping his opponent's forces at bay we see numerous examples of Gukesh using pinning tactics to devastating effect. Pins are a great way of immobilising pieces, the pinned pieces can't move without exposing more valuable pieces, and the opponent's other forces may also get tied down to the defence of the pinned piece. 4. Sacrifices Among other players, Gukesh studied the games of Veselin Topalov to understand how the Bulgarian Grandmaster used sacrifices. Sacrificing to open lines against the opponent's king - Depending on the merits of the position Gukesh may choose to attack with pawns, pieces or positional play. In this section, expect to see violent piece sacrifices to reach the opposing king. Exchange sacrifices - An AlphaZero theme, Gukesh is very aware of the dynamic value of pieces. Gukesh will often sacrifice a rook for an active enemy minor piece in the endgame if that will give him a positional advantage such as passed pawns that are difficult to stop - and this combines very well with another Guki-Style-Factor: Advanced pawns. 5. Co-ordination The way Gukesh co-ordinated his two knights against Wei Yiâs rook to reach a winning position at the 2024 Olympiad prompted commentator GM Daniel Naroditsky to say: âThis is an achievement that Magnus Carlsen would consider among his best. This endgame conversion was un-freaking-believable.â Knights co-ordination - Gukesh often brings both of his knights into the attack together in coordinated fashion. Opening a diagonal to support an attack along a file, or vice versa - Gukesh frequently achieves open lines and play for his pieces and this AlphaZero technique is used to make the attack more powerful than just using a file or diagonal on its own. It's a case where the sum is more than its parts. Controlling a colour complex - Gukesh will play against weaknesses anywhere on the board but especially around his opponent's king. One such weakness is when the opponent finds it difficult to control or defend squares of one colour. This could be because their pawns cannot defend that colour square, perhaps that coloured square bishop has been exchanged, or the short range pieces are far away. Gukesh will look to infiltrate that colour for an easy way to the opponent's king. 6. Complexity As Gukesh told New In Chess in 2019: 'I really like playing 'crazy' positions with head-spinning complications.' Crazy positions - Gukesh loves complexity and crazy positions can result. This gives the chance for either player to make mistakes, and Gukesh will steer the game this way to avoid draws, and because he is strong in these types of positions, and simply enjoys them! Nerves of steel - Gukesh is cool and calm at the board. He calculates long lines to know that although his king may be exposed he will have enough time to conduct his attack first elsewhere on the board. In other games he allows his opponent to get a pawn to the 7th rank, or even promote, while remaining totally unruffled. Zwischenzugs - You will find many examples of intermediate moves, or intermezzos as they are sometimes known, throughout this course. The themes in actionThis game is Hector Giacomini - Gukesh Dommaraju, Reykjavik 2019. } 
1.Nf3  Nf6  
2.e3  g6  
3.d4  Bg7  
4.c4  O-O  
5.Be2  d6  
6.Nc3  Nbd7  
7.O-O  e5  { A King's Indian Defence. We can expect to see White expanding on the queenside and Gukesh as Black attacking on the kingside - and this is exactly what happens. } 
8.b4  Re8  
9.a4  e4  
10.Nd2  Nf8  
11.a5  a6  
12.b5  h5  
13.Bb2  h4  { The advance of the h-pawn, AlphaZero-style. } 
14.h3  N8h7  
15.Qb3  Ng5  
16.Rfc1  Be6  
17.Qd1  Qd7  
18.Bf1  Bf5  
19.Nd5  Nxd5  { This exchange allows Gukesh to keep the centre relatively closed, giving Gukesh more freedom to advance his kingside pawns without worry. } 
20.cxd5  axb5  
21.Qb3  Qe7  
22.Qxb5  Rab8  
23.Rc2  Nh7  { This knight is on a long journey, see where it ends up in a few moves from now. } 
24.Rac1  Rec8  
25.Ba3  Nf6  
26.Be2  g5  { Gukesh advances another pawn in front of his castled king. } 
27.Nf1  g4  
28.hxg4  Nxg4  
29.Nh2  Nxh2  { The knight that was on [h7] a few moves ago is exchanged for one of White's few remaining kingside defenders. } 
30.Kxh2  Bh6  
31.Bb4  Kh8  
32.Bf1  Bg4  
33.Be1  f5  
34.a6  bxa6  
35.Qxa6  f4  { Advancing another pawn on the kingside. Notice how we have the type of position we are becoming accustomed to in the hands of Gukesh - Black has left his king by itself in the corner with only long-range protection from pawns and little cover from any pieces. However, it is safe at the moment, shielded by the central pawn wall, because White's pieces are far away and stuck on the other side of it. Will the pressure of the queen and doubled rooks against the c-pawn allow White to get through later? Gukesh correctly judges that he will be quick enough. } 
36.Bd2  { The engine top choice for White is to counterattack via capturing the [c7] pawn and infiltrating the 7th rank. } ( { There are several ways to play, but it seems to be fine to just let it happen: } 36.Qa7 Rf8 37.Rxc7 Qf6 38.Rh7+ Kg8 39.Qe7 fxe3 40.Qxf6 Rxf6 { and Black still has the threat of capturing on [f2], so White is best to give up the exchange on [h6], but this leaves Black with a winning endgame. } ) h3  { White's king cannot run away from the advancing pawns. } 
37.gxh3  ( 37.g3 fxg3+ 38.fxg3 Rf8 { threatens to penetrate via the f-file. White cannot meet this by taking the pawn on [c7] because: } 39.Rxc7 Rf2+ 40.Kg1 h2+ {(leads eventually to a forced checkmate.)} ) Qh4  ( { Gukesh likes to activate his queen and this move helps to build up his attack. On this occasion, there are several moves that the engine prefers, and the top two choices are: } 37...Rg8! { and } {37...Bf3!} ) 
38.Be1  f3  
39.Rxc7  Rg8  
40.Qxd6  { White has a rook on the 7th rank and a queen on the 6th and yet Gukesh is still not worried. He can now execute a tactic to win material. } Bxh3  { Black has mating threats thanks to his rook and the queen. } 
41.Qg3  Qxg3+  ( { Gukesh's move is clearly good enough for the win. The natural } 41...Rxg3 { is even stronger! } ) 
42.fxg3  Bxf1  { Black has won a piece and Gukesh went on to win. } 
43.Bf2  Bg2  
44.R1c6  Bg5  
45.g4  Rb1  
46.Rc1  Rxc1  
47.Rxc1  Kg7  
48.Rc7+  Kf6  
49.Rh7  Kg6  
50.Rh5  Rd8  
51.Bh4  Rxd5  
52.Kg3  Bxh4+  
53.Rxh4  Ra5  
54.Rh8  Ra3  
55.Kf2  Ra2+  
56.Kg3  Bf1  
57.d5  Rg2+  
58.Kf4  f2  { This game was played in round 1 of the Reykjavik Open 2019 in which Gukesh scored 6/9. Also achieving 6/9 were brother and sister Praggnanandhaa and Vaishali. } { Hector Giacomini, from France, has had a peak rating of 2290. }  0-1


[Event "Masterful Moves: Gukesh"]
[White "1) Gukesh's style"]
[Black "1a. Advanced pawns: Far-advanced pawns"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/2PP1p2/pp4p1/2p2q1p/Qn1bp2P/6B1/P3BPP1/2R2RK1 b - - 0 1"]

{ Far-advanced pawnsWe have very often seen Gukesh with pawns advanced far up the board. The first example against Tari is a startling position, and it is well worth playing through the whole game as you can see how he forced the pawns through the centre - at one stage of the game there is a stand-off with three white pawns facing three black pawns in the centre. A successful pawn advance can wreak havoc in the opponent's camp, and provided the pawn can be kept safe - which Gukesh often achieves through tactical means - an advanced pawn is highly valuable as it may turn into a queen, or force the opponent to give up material to stop it. Gukesh combines pawn advances with other tactics; there are several examples of Gukesh giving up rook for a minor piece in the Sacrifices section, if that means that he can obtain strong passed pawns, and the Sargissian game in this section includes a Zwischenzug. Gukesh Dommaraju - Aryan Tari, Stavanger 2023 - also shown here. Gukesh starts with two far-advanced pawns and is able to use them to win material even though Black is attempting distraction tactics against his queen. Gukesh Dommaraju - Ortik Nigmatov, 2022 Gukesh, playing White, has sacrificed a pawn in order to pursue his attack, and he lines up against the [h7] pawn threatening mate. Black has an interesting response - to sacrifice the queen to prevent mate, with the plan of winning back White's queen in return. White is able to take countermeasures using his perfectly placed advanced pawn however. With a well timed check on [f7] the pawn deflects Black's rook to an unsafe square, and Gukesh is able to return the queen, simplify, and then capture the rook. Gukesh Dommaraju - Gabriel Sargissian 2022 At the start of this position it looks like White's e-pawn is sure to be traded off. With a clever intermediate move, Gukesh manages to gain time to bring his queen to the g-file with powerful effect, and Black has to seek an exchange of queens. This leaves White's rooks unopposed on the g-file, but it is the heroic e-pawn that allows White to break through. Carlsen, Magnus - Gukesh Dommaraju 2023 Gukesh is Black against Magnus Carlsen in a blitz game. Material is down to just a knight and two pawns each, and it is a race to queen. Carlsen has central pawns and Gukesh wing pawns. With a knight check at the right moment, Gukesh is able to stop either the king or knight reaching his a-pawn, and he sees it home to the queening square. Gukesh Dommaraju - Maxime Vachier-Lagrave 2023 Gukesh has left his king in the centre while building up his position. MVL tries a rook sacrifice to stir up trouble before White can complete his development. Gukesh stays calm and basically ignores Black, instead counterattacking with his a-pawn. Black also ignores White, and Black takes material while White queens. Gukesh had seen further. The newly-created queen is able to give a check to pick up the errant black rook. Move from Gukesh - Tari, 2023: } b5  
2.Bxb5  {[%csl Bc7]} {[%csl Bd7]}  *


[Event "Masterful Moves: Gukesh"]
[White "1) Gukesh's style"]
[Black "1b. Advanced pawns: Pushing pawns in front of the castled king"]
