[FEN "1r2k2r/2pn1pp1/q1bp3p/2n1pP2/p1P1P1P1/8/PP1BQNBP/1R2R1K1 w k - 0 1"]

{ Pushing pawns in front of the castled kingGukesh has always enjoyed advancing his kingside pawns and he is still doing it at the time of writing in 2024! We often see him advancing his g-pawn to kick away a piece, and his f-pawn to gain space. And we have a whole section next on his use of the h-pawn. The benefits of these advances are that it gives his pieces more space and activity, and can cramp the opponent. We sometimes see a large amount of space around his king, but that his frontier of pawns is also reinforced with pieces so that nothing can get behind.... or at least if an enemy piece gets in it will be too slow! Jerish John Velarde - Gukesh Dommaraju 2015 Gukesh frequently advanced his kingside pawns, even when he was very little. He had done so here and we reach a relatively simplified position where White has a knight not too far from Gukesh's king, and Black has his bishop bolstering his pawn chain. It is a case of misadventure as the knight is impeded by Black's pawns, has no squares, and is lost. Gukesh Dommaraju - Jaime Santos Latasa, 2018 Gukesh has advanced his kingside pawns and gained space. It looks as if the c-file will be an avenue for attack but Gukesh switches attention back to the kingside, advancing his queen and his knight there. Although there is a big space around White's king, the black pieces are not able to enter as the front is well defended. Gukesh continues his pawn advance, and using an intermediate check from a pawn on [f6], is able to engineer a position where mate is unavoidable. Volodar Murzin - Gukesh Dommaraju, 2019 Gukesh has built up a phalanx of pawns in the centre and on the kingside, and - relying on a pin - he finds a way to mobilise them, and comes out with a dangerous passed d-pawn. When he has that, nothing else matters, not even his bishop, and Gukesh sees it home for the win. Gukesh Dommaraju - Harutyun Barseghyan 2020 It looks as if White is in some trouble with the opponent's queen, bishop and knight attacking the kingside, where Gukesh has advanced his pawns. Aided by a mistake from his opponent Gukesh manages to turn the tables, starting with setting up a pin, and finding a safe spot near his advanced pawns for his king - on [h3] } { (a square AlphaZero often liked to put its king on) } { . Then he engineers a discovered attack to win material. If you are wondering whether this approach is one he uses only against lower-rated opponents in open tournaments, here he is advancing his kingside pawns, and winning, at the 2022 Olympiad against one of the highest-rated players in the world: Fabiano Caruana - Gukesh Dommaraju 2022 Gukesh is elevating his position against Caruana, by which we mean that he advances his pawns and advances his pieces with them. This can cramp the opponent, particularly if an intact wall of advanced pawns can be maintained. Black has a powerful queen on [d5] and builds up with rooks on the a-file, and even back rank possibilities in the air, until White feels the need to break out with [g4]. Gukesh then switches plans to get his light squared bishop into position and takes advantage of the weakened light squares. Gukesh Dommaraju - Andrey Tsvetkov, Sochi 2019 Gukesh forces back the Black queen with tempo with the move [g4], and continues targeting it even after it has retreated, firstly with Gukesh's advanced e-pawn and then with his rook. Something has to cave in. Moves from Gukesh - Barseghyan 2020: } 
1.h4   *


[Event "Masterful Moves: Gukesh"]
