{ Active queenAn active queen is a big priority for Gukesh. Activity could be getting the queen into a position with a lot of space and freedom to move. We would also consider a queen to be active when in easy reach of its target - in Gukesh's case his target is often the opponent's king, though it could also be loose pieces, weak pawns or important squares. Naturally, it is important for all of our army to be active. We have chosen the queen as the example to focus on here, as this is the one piece where activity has the biggest impact. Thinking about it in very simplistic terms - when we start to play we are taught a queen is worth 9 points. If it is restricted to lose a third of its movement, that's about a 3 point loss - it is as if at that moment we are a piece down! We noticed that Gukesh nearly always has an active queen, and if he doesn't, he takes measures to activate it. In our examples, we see him moving pieces out of the way, and even sacrificing material to get his queen active. Gukesh Dommaraju - Fy Antenaina Rakotomaharo 2020 Also shown here. After finding an unlikely but highly effective starting move, Gukesh is able to activate his queen from a blocked diagonal, out into the middle of the board, and then on to be the key checkmating piece. Fabiano Caruana - Gukesh Dommaraju - 2022 In a complex position in the 2022 Olympiad, Gukesh brings his queen to the most active square. Caruana's position soon collapses and Gukesh finishes it off with a nice mating threat. Gukesh Dommaraju - Anand Pranav 2023. Gukesh sacrifices a piece in order to ensure his queen stays active. Needless to say, he gets back the material with interest. The moves shown are from Gukesh - Rakotomaharo: } 
1.Nh7+  Ke7  
2.Qh4+  f6  
3.Qb4+  Ke8  
4.Qd6  Bc4  
5.Qc7  {[%cal Bh3h4]} {[%cal Bh4b4]} {[%cal Bb4d6]} {[%cal Bd6c7]}  *


