{ Use of the whole boardIn the previous sections we have already seen many examples of far advanced pawns, including rook's pawn pushes which forms a part of Gukesh's use of the extremes of the chess board. In this section, we focus on pieces travelling the board, and often to squares at the edge. We start off with a couple of examples of Gukesh bringing a knight into the action from a long way away across the board. We go on to see knights moving to the side of the board and back rank. And then a rather nice game against Adhiban, where Gukesh's bishop wanders around some seemingly impossible squares. Gukesh Dommaraju - Bjorn Ahlander 2019 - also shown here. This is a beautiful example of using the whole board. Gukesh advances both of his rook's pawns - the a-pawn creates queening threats, and the h-pawn opens up an avenue of attack along the g-file. And then his knight embarks on a selfless and rather deep manoeuvre. First it gets out of the way of the g-file meaning that the bishop on [e7] needs to stay put to defend. It finds its way in to [e6] creating several threats, and finally sacrifices itself on [c7] to allow the major pieces to deliver mate. Gukesh Dommaraju - Marcus Harvey 2018 Gukesh correctly calculates that his far-away knight will be able to stop Black's passed pawn in the endgame. Gukesh Dommaraju - Vladimir Dobrov 2020 Gukesh puts both of the knights at the edge of the board. He had calculated that he could create deadly threats this way, overloading the queen that is needed to defend both [b7] and [f6]. Artur Davtyan - Gukesh Dommaraju - 2021. Gukesh uses his queen and knights together to activate his queen while keeping the opposing queen restricted in movement. Alireza Firouzja - Gukesh Dommaraju 2023 A brilliant knight manoeuvre ends in White having to give up his rook for it on the back rank. Look out also for Black's active queen! Gukesh Dommaraju - Adhiban Baskaran, 2022 Gukesh must have enjoyed this game where his bishop wanders immune through the innards of Black's position, picking up two pawns en route, before emerging with an intermediate move to a capture. Move here from Gukesh - Ahlander: } gxh6  {[%cal Bg3h5]} {[%cal Bh5f4]} {[%cal Bf4e6]} {[%cal Be6c7]} 
2.Nh5  e4  
3.Qxe4  Qxa6  
4.Nf4  Ke8  
5.Ne6  Rc8  
6.Rg8+  Kd7  
7.Qd5+  Bd6  
8.Rg7+  Ke8  
9.Nc7+  {[%csl Gg3]} {[%cal Gg3h5]} {[%csl Gh5]} {[%cal Gh5f4]} {[%csl Gf4]} {[%cal Gf4e6]} {[%csl Ge6]} {[%cal Ge6c7]} {[%csl Gc7]}  *


