{ The opposing king is restrictedWe say that a king is restricted if it cannot legally move at all, or if it has very limited movement. If a king is stuck in a restricted position, it can become very vulnerable because a simple check could be enough to be checkmate - the king cannot move away. Gukesh likes to restrict his opponent's king, and once it is immobile he will concentrate his efforts in then targeting the king as it can be much easier than you might think, to deliver checkmate - or to set up threats to do so that the opponent has to make compromises to meet. Our examples show young Gukesh exchanging off queens but still getting winning mating threats. Make sure you play through Gukesh's game against Robert Hess, as this contains masterful restriction of the whole white army, achieved during a blitz game. Gukesh Dommaraju - Neeraj Kumar Mishra 2017 The 11-year-old Gukesh allows his important central pawn to be taken, and for queens to be exchanged, in order that he activates his bishop and creates unstoppable mating threats. The restricted position of Black's king, confined to the corner, meant this tactic could work. Nico Chasin - Gukesh Dommaraju 2018 It is reaching the endgame. Both sides have queens, and Black has a useful bishop pair facing off to White's bishop and knight. When White goes after a pawn, Gukesh wastes no time in advancing the e-pawn to support the activation of his queen. His queen and bishop directly attack the king, which becomes very restricted in movement. In the end, the only way White can parry a check is to give up his queen. Robert Hess - Gukesh Dommaraju 2020 The whole game is impressive from Gukesh in the level of control that he is able to achieve. White's king and queen both become very short of squares, and Gukesh is again able to activate his own queen to finish things off. Moves from Gukesh - Kumar Mishra 2017: } Qxe4  
2.Qxe4  Bxe4  
3.Bf7  {[%cal Bf7g8]} {[%csl Rg8]} {[%cal Bh6g7]} {[%csl Rg7]} {[%cal Bg3g8]}  *


