{ PinsEverybody uses pins, but we were impressed by the frequency and power of the pins in Gukesh's games. Here are examples of just some of the pins with rooks and bishops that we found. This fits in with a strategy of restraint: the opponent's pinned pieces cannot move, but also their other pieces will be tied down to defence. Be sure to see the pin against Matthieu Cornette which sets up a Zugzwang. Gukesh Dommaraju - Matthieu Cornette 2019 A pin on the c-file decides the game. Gukesh ties up all of Black's major pieces in defending, to such an extent that he can set up a Zugswang and win the pinned piece. Gukesh Dommaraju - Daniel Romero Pollares 2022 Gukesh had a rook in an advanced position in a major piece endgame. By dropping it backwards he found a new and effective line of attack, and was able to win Black's queen with a pin. Gukesh Dommaraju - Nico Georgiadis 2022 - position shown here. Just out of the opening, Gukesh attacks a pawn and is able to win it through a combination of pin, deflection and overload of the enemy queen. Anish Giri - Gukesh Dommaraju 2023 - also shown in the diagram here. Both a bishop pin and a rook pin are involved. Gukesh uses the setup of his rook opposing the white king, which makes a bishop pin on [c3] possible } { (pinning the rook to the queen) } { . The bishop cannot be taken because Black would then have fatal threats against the white king. Gukesh doesn't take the rook immediately but brings in the queen first before capturing the pinned rook. Mohammad Minhaz Uddin - Gukesh Dommaraju 2021 Again a bishop pin and a rook pin combine to win material. This time Gukesh finds a knight move that directly attacks one pinned piece, and uncovers an attack on another. White defends, and Gukesh attacks the defender. We reach a position with three white pieces en prise and Gukesh emerges with extra material. Gukesh Dommaraju - Petar Kovac 2018 The black knight occupies a central outpost and Gukesh takes countermeasures with a shocking capture of a central pawn - White's knight cannot be captured because of a bishop pinning the black queen along the [a2] to [g8] diagonal. Alexander Donchenko - Gukesh Dommaraju 2024 A very nice tactic involving a bishop pin, and then a cross pin, relying on the white queen being undefended. Gukesh Dommaraju - Rameshbabu Praggnanandha, 2023 This tactic is all about calculating to the end of the line. It looks as if Praggnanandha has orchestrated a trick, but the last twist uses a pin and is in Gukesh's favour. Moves here from Gukesh - Georgiadis: } 
1.b3  b5  {[%cal Bc8c2]} {[%cal Be6d5]} {[%cal Rc4b5]}  *


