{ Sacrifices to win the endgameGukesh's prowess as a great tactician and fearsome attacker is well known, but his style also gives rise to some fantastic endgame play! His penchant for far advanced pawns ties in with another type of sacrifice that we frequently see him undertake - a sacrifice that results in him winning the endgame. The following examples all show Gukesh sacrificing an exchange to leave him with unstoppable pawns! Gukesh Dommaraju - Krishnater Kushager 2018 Gukesh sacrifices the exchange, giving up a rook for Black's most active piece: his knight. Gukesh reasons that he will have two strong passed pawns and lots of mobility for his bishop and rook, whereas Black's rooks are blockading pawns. Gukesh Dommaraju - Koustav Chatterjee, 2019 Gukesh sacrifices his rook for Black's far advanced knight, knowing that he will be left with the far superior pawn structure and a good bishop. Although on this occasion he doesn't yet have passed pawns, it is only a matter of time because Black's weak pawns will be picked off one by one. Koustav Chatterjee - Gukesh Dommaraju 2022 This endgame sacrifice saw Gukesh giving up the exchange in order to get passed rooks pawns, and to constrain his opponent's king to the back rank. Krishnan Sasikiran - Gukesh Dommaraju 2022 This time Gukesh has pushed his queenside pawns up the board. He has strong connected passed pawns if he can get rid of the pawn on [c3]. The solution? An exchange sacrifice to open up the diagonal and capture it. Black went on to win in just a few moves. Moves from Gukesh - Krishnater 2018: } Rcd7  
2.Rxc6  bxc6  
