{ Knights co-ordinationFollowing Gukesh's celebrated and beautiful endgame against Wei Yi from the Budapest 2024 Olympiad, we looked at how Gukesh uses his knights in a co-ordinated fashion. We bring you that Wei Yi game, and also a lovely endgame from a Chess960 game that Gukesh won against Magnus Carlsen, also from 2024. Gukesh also co-ordinates his knights in the middle game, and here we show several examples of his use of the 're-loader' - see below. Two knights in the endgame Gukesh Dommaraju - Wei Yi 2024 Live commentary teams had given up this position as a draw, and were questioning Gukesh's judgment when he had two knights against a rook, and went into a line that gave up his a-pawn - as it then felt like both sides had chances. Gukesh summoned his nerves of steel and found move after move the narrow path to victory, in this crucial game which secured the Indian team's win against China. Gukesh Dommaraju - Magnus Carlsen 2024 Carlsen has had to give up a piece to stop Gukesh's advanced pawn - yes it's still a feature even in his Chess960 games! - and Gukesh is left with two knights and a rook against Carlsen's rook and bishop. Gukesh achieves great co-ordination between the knights, controlling all of the squares the king could advance to, and he is able to force the king to the back rank and win the game. The reloader 'The reloader' is a term coined by FM Martin Weteschnik in his book and online course Chess Tactics from Scratch. Here, it involves bringing in the second knight to renew the same, or similar, threats from the same square that the first knight had just been occupying. Aryan Polakhare - Gukesh Dommaraju 2016 Gukesh spots that White has a weakness on the [a7]-[g1] diagonal leading to the king, and that hence White's knight on [d4] is inadequately defended. Gukesh temporarily gives up a knight on [e3] to exploit this. Then, rather than immediately recapture he reloads his other knight to [g4] and then [e3] which results in him winning more material. Gukesh Dommaraju - Aleksandra Maltsevskaya 2018 Gukesh gives up both knights in the opening for a rook and two pawns. A balanced position results but Gukesh has open lines and is able to make the most of his play. Leon Mendonca - Gukesh Dommaraju 2021 Gukesh wins a loose piece by invading with one of his knights, exchanging it off, and then reloading with the other knight, which then naturally attacks the recapturing piece. Moves from Gukesh - Maltsevskaya 2018: } c5  
2.Ndb5  axb5  
3.Nxb5  Qb8  
4.Nxd6   *


