{ Opening a diagonal to support an attack along a file, or vice versaThese positions are all about how Gukesh co-ordinates his bishops and rooks together. They are also about line clearance so that his long-range pieces can operate effectively, and there are parallels to some of the themes we already saw in the section on Activity, including prioritising the activity of his pieces, even if it needs a sacrifice to do it. Gukesh Dommaraju - Rajkumar S 2017 This is a very nice sequence with a little surprise in the middle to set up a windmill combination of bishop checking on the long diagonal while the rook does damage. Gukesh Dommaraju - Minh Hieu Hoang, Chiangmai 2018 Gukesh sets up a bishop fork along the [a5]-[d8] diagonal, but needs to be able to unblock the c-file to execute it. He gives up a pawn and gets his dream. Gukesh Dommaraju - Alejandro Bofill Mas, Barcelona 2018 The file is the h-file and the diagonal is [b1] to [h7]. By moving his bishop to the diagonal, Gukesh frees a safe square for his king, meaning that the h-file can be cleared and the rook and bishop combine - forcing Black to advance his g-pawn to defend, at which point Gukesh gets a strong attack. Position from Gukesh - Hoang 2018: } 
1.b4  {[%cal Bc1c7]} {[%cal Bf4c7]} {[%csl Rc7]}  *


