{ Controlling a colour complexWe cover two examples with clear instructive play, resulting from situations where Gukesh has a choice of bishop recapture. In these examples, he opts for positions where he judges that he will be able to attack strongly and win material. This is because he is able to exploit a weak colour complex around the opponent's king, which becomes more vulnerable when the defending bishop is exchanged. Gukesh Dommaraju - Susanto Megaranto 2019 When his bishop is attacked, Gukesh doesn't retreat it but instead captures Black's dark-squared bishop, with the plan of exploiting the weak dark squares around Black's king. He uses threats against [g7] and deflection tactics to win pawns, and Black resigned. Pawel Teclaf - Gukesh Dommaraju 2021 Offered a choice of bishops to capture Gukesh takes White's light-squared bishop with a view to playing against the light squares [g2], [f3] and [h3]. The resulting opposite-coloured bishops position is in theory about equal, but his opponent doesn't see the danger in time and Gukesh is able to win in just a few moves. Moves from Teclaf - Gukesh 2021: } 
