{ Crazy positionsGukesh told World Chess in an interview in 2023: âWhy I like chess is because of how complex it is, how itâs been played for so many years and how people still donât understand it - itâs always amusing for me. There are limited possibilities, but humans find it so hard to play, I donât know why.â Gukesh's fascination for the complexity of chess, and his willingness to roll with the complications rather than simplify or accept a drawish line, leads to many wild and double-edged games, which are excellent entertainment for the viewer. Using his legendary calculation skills, and also the positional factors that we have already seen, such as creating activity for himself, and restricting the opponent, Gukesh backs himself to finish on top in complex struggles. Karthik Venkataraman - Gukesh Dommaraju, 2022 Gukesh playing Black gave up one central pawn and offered another in order to reach a position where White's king hasn't quite found safety and White's pieces are a little disconnected and haven't found harmony. Gukesh takes immediate action, occupying the c-file and bringing in major pieces to assist his advanced d-pawn. While White tries to coordinate, Black offers a knight, but it can't really be taken and Black's forces are able to infiltrate the 2nd rank. Gukesh Dommaraju - Vincent Keymer, 2024 This position has a lot of Guki-Style-Factors such as advanced pawns, pins, and allowing the opponent to get on with their plan because Gukesh is simply not scared of it. Black threatens to win White's queen, and Gukesh responds by opening lines against Black's queen, including via pushing a pawn to [g7] to open a line for his bishop. Gukesh's attack proves the stronger. Wei Yi - Gukesh Dommaraju, 2024 In an exciting and brilliant game with Wei Yi we do get the trademark Gukesh king on [h8], his pawns advanced, and enemy pieces closer than his own. The pieces do seem to be showered across the board, and Gukesh wins material tactically before forcing a trade of queens to keep himself safe - and he converts. Moves here from Gukesh - Keymer: } 
1.hxg4  Rxc4  
2.Rxf6+   *


