{ Nerves of steelGukesh's calm appearance at the board belies the bravery that he shows on the 64 squares. He loves complex positions, and he trusts his own calculations and assessment of the positions - due to not using an engine to analyse when he was younger - so it is very hard to bluff him. This means we often see Gukesh allow his opponent to execute their plan, provided that Gukesh's own plan will be stronger and quicker. It can look as if Gukesh is getting his king into danger, or leaving it exposed, but usually! Gukesh will have it all worked out and under control. Asked in an interview with Firstpost where his boldness comes from, he replied: âThe truth is I donât really know where it comes from because being brave is not something that you can practise, itâs just a way of living life, I guess. From a very young age with my mum we used to talk a lot of mental stuffâ¦ and before sleeping she used to always say to me that Iâm going to achieve all my goals.â Gukesh Dommaraju - Dias Alimbetov 2014 The young Gukesh parries a check by bringing his king up the board. He continues his kingside attack and Black's king, despite being the more tucked away, is severely outnumbered by white pieces and falls quickly. Ilja Semjonovs - Gukesh Dommaraju 2018 Gukesh correctly decides the safest way to defend an onslaught by White's queen and rook is to bring his king out into the open. Only when he has challenged for the open h-file does he retreat back behind his pawn cover. Jan-Krzysztof Duda - Gukesh Dommaraju 2024 It looks as if Duda has a very dangerous attack, with a queen and two bishops pointing directly at the black king. Gukesh decides now is the time to capture an enemy knight, and then stroll away with his king to safety. Gukesh - Praggnanandhaa 2024 In this rapid play game, Praggnanandha has sacrificed a knight for some very dangerous play, including his rook coming in to White's position, and a bishop lined up in the long diagonal against White's king. Gukesh accepts the material and holds on tight, emerging material ahead after some nervous moments. Gukesh Dommaraju - Parham Maghsoodloo, 2023 Gukesh has an advanced passed a-pawn, but Black's pieces are bearing down on his king. Gukesh organises his defence to include the advance of his g-pawn, and then he attacks Black's king with his queen and bishop. Maghsoodloo mis-steps by trying to open the position further, and Gukesh is then able to bring his rook into play by overloading Black's knight. Moves from Semjonovs - Gukesh 2018: } 
1.Rh3  h5  
2.g4  hxg4  
3.Qh6+  Kf6  
4.Qh4+  Kf5  {[%csl Gf5]} {[%cal Be8h8]}  *


[Event "Masterful Moves: Gukesh"]
[White "1) Gukesh's style"]
[Black "6c. Complexity: Zwischenzugs"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2kr4/pppr2b1/7p/6p1/1PP3P1/3n1N2/P1Bn1P2/3R1RK1 w - - 0 1"]

{ ZwischenzugsYou may be familiar with our Chessable course Zwischenzug!. If not, do check it out - you will soon be thinking about intermediate moves in a whole new way!! A Zwischenzug is a move that interrupts the normal - or expected - sequence, and typically poses a threat in the hope of gaining an advantage. These exciting, and sometimes shocking, moves abound in the type of rich and crazy positions that Gukesh aims for. It is therefore no surprise that we have found numerous intermediate moves within Gukesh's combinations. We also noticed that Gukesh is extremely good at spotting Zwischenzugs, it appears that he rarely misses them! We describe a few of Gukesh's intermezzos below, and for fun we have used the names that we introduced to categorise Zwischenzugs in our earlier course. Alvar Alonso Rosell - Gukesh, Dommaraju, 2022 White had a promising late middle-game position with the bishop pair, but his queen was somewhat out of play. He attacked Gukesh's rook, aiming to gain a tempo to fully reactivate his queen. Gukesh ignored the attack on his rook and instead brought his bishop out, to deflect White's key defender of the weak [f2]-square. This is an 'Accelerate the Attack' intermezzo. Gukesh's plan worked - the white bishop was distracted, and Gukesh is able to take on [f2] and then move his rook. The sting in the tail is that White is still unable to move his bishop without allowing Black to invade the second rank. LÃª Quang LiÃªm - Gukesh Dommaraju, 2021 We call this type of Zwischenzug a 'Pin before Recapture' - a simple idea, but it can be easy to miss! White offers a trade of bishops which would also appear to result in a trade of pawns. Gukesh starts out by taking the offered pawn, and his opponent continues with the bishop trade. However, Gukesh does not immediately recapture the bishop, but instead pins it first, to later recapture, and by doing it this way he wins a pawn. Gukesh Dommaraju - Tor Fredrik Kaasen, 2021 Intermediate moves can be defensive and this is a 'Stop Attack or Counterplay Zwischenzug'. In this game Gukesh launches an attack with a sacrificial sequence which culminates in Gukesh skewering Black's queen to his rook. Along the way though, there was a possibility of Black evading capture if his rook could escape with check. Gukesh saw the possibility and prevented it by playing his own intermediate queen check to ensure that his defences were sound. Gukesh Dommaraju - Nils Grandelius, online 2021 Grandelius advances his queen, attacking and threatening to trade queens into an endgame. Instead of responding, Gukesh sacrifices the exchange on [g7], a 'Deflection Zwischenzug' crucially with check, giving himself time to bring in his queen, also with check, and then the other rook, to create unstoppable threats. Giga Quparadze - Gukesh Dommaraju, 2023 A second example of a 'Deflection Zwischenzug' here combined with a legendary Gukesh pin. White aims to trap Black by luring his queen to a square where it can be forked by the white knight. Gukesh has an intermediate move prepared which sacrifices a rook to deflect the king to [h1] - meaning that White's knight is pinned and can no longer perpetrate its fork. Savalkar Aditya - Gukesh, Dommaraju 2016 - also shown here. This is an early Gukesh tactic that wins material, and it includes a common Zwischenzug pattern that we have named 'Connected Rooks'. Gukesh engineers the pattern on the d-file - one of his rooks, which is defended, facing off against an undefended opponent rook, with a piece in between, in this case Gukesh's knight. Black is able to move the knight out of the way forcing White to capture Gukesh's rook. Then comes the intermediate move... the knight moves again, capturing the opponent's knight with check, giving time for Black to return and also recapture the rook. Thai Dai Van Nguyen - Gukesh Dommaraju 2024 This tactical sequence is especially nice because it seems to come out of nowhere - a fairly quiet endgame it would appear - and then Gukesh spots sets a deadly pin. It would appear that White can escape by attacking Black's rook but the Gukesh finds a beautiful pawn advance to attack White's rook too - we call it a 'Mutual Rooks En Prise Zwischenzug' - and that combined with snap mating threats was enough to give Black the win! Gukesh Dommaraju - Valeriy Grinev 2018 This 'Mutual Queens En Prise Zwischenzug' enabled Gukesh to hold firm and avoid retreating his queen when it was attacked. Instead, he was able to advance a pawn which opened a line against Black's queen while simultaneously attacking the black knight. The upshot? Gukesh won material. Gukesh Dommaraju - Vuppala Prraneeth, 2016 Gukesh's bishop has been attacked. Instead of moving it Gukesh first plays his rook to the e-file pinning the black queen to the king. It can be defended but the threats along the e-file mean that White is then able to win a pawn rather than meekly retreat his bishop. We call this a 'Rook to the Open file Zwischenzug'. Look out for this tactic! We have seen it occurring in many positions where at first sight a threat must be parried, but it turns out that a simple move to develop your rook can defend, or can create dangerous counter-threats. As you progress through this course, do look out for even more examples of Zwischenzugs. Moves here from Aditya - Gukesh, 2016: } 
1.Rxd2  {[%cal Bd3e5]} {[%cal Be5f3]} {[%cal Bf3g1]} {[%csl Rg1]} {[%cal Bd7d2]} {[%cal Bd2d7]} {[%csl Rd2]} {[%csl Gd7]} Ne5  
2.Rxd7  Nxf3+  
3.Kh1  Kxd7   *


