{ FIDE rating August 2013: 1291 }  { FIDE rating December 2013: 1303 }  { FIDE rating December 2014: 1600 }  { FIDE rating December 2015: 2041 }  { FIDE rating December 2016: 2236 }  { FIDE-rated standard-play games: 282 } { Here is where it all began. 2013: first FIDE rating Gukesh began playing chess at school and at home, after watching his parents play the game, and from the age of six he was competing in tournaments. He quickly became an active player: the chess-results.com website records 'Gukesh D' participating in 100 tournaments from 2013-2016, equivalent to almost one every other week and there may have been even more events that were not recorded. One of the earliest high-profile events he played in was the National Under-7 Open in Pune which took place at the start of May 2013, a few weeks before Gukesh's seventh birthday. He scored 6.5/11. The winner was Aditya Mittal, who became a Grandmaster in 2023. Gukeshâs first FIDE rating of 1291 was awarded in August 2013 after he competed in two rating tournaments in July. Both tournaments had more than 600 competitors, which gives you an idea of the size of such events in India. 2014: an early role model At the age of seven, Gukesh attended a tournament where Rameshbabu Praggnanandhaa and his sister Vaishali were introduced to the young players at the opening ceremony. Praggnanandhaa, almost a year older than Gukesh, had recently won the World Youth Chess Championship Under-8 title in late December 2013 with a score of 11/11. The year before, Vaishali had won the Under-12 Girls' title. The sibling pair's success was celebrated at the tournament which cemented Praggnanandhaa as an early role model and inspiration for Gukesh. Eight years later, both boys would play in the same India team in the 2022 Olympiad. Gukesh's first games in the Chessbase MegaDatabase are from 2014 when he took part in the World Youth Chess Championships in Durban, South Africa. In the under 8 section, he lined up in a field of 64 that included Indian compatriot Leon Mendonca who was to become a Grandmaster in 2021 and Rajat Makkar of France at the time of writing in 2024 an International Master. Gukesh achieved 8/11 and fifth place, which matched his starting rank. The tournament winner was Russian Ilya Makoveev, who became a FIDE Master in 2018. 2015: first tournament in Singapore The 2024 World Championship match will not be Gukeshâs first chess event in Singapore. He will have fond memories of his visit to the same country nine years earlier. In May and June 2015 Singapore played host to the 11th Asian School Chess Championships. Gukesh competed in the under 9 section where he was ranked number one with his rating of 1772, more than 200 ahead of the next competitor. Thanks to seven wins and two draws, he won the tournament with 8/9 and also earned the candidate master CM title. This year also featured a key moment in Gukeshâs development. He was still attending school full-time, but Vishy Anand told his parents that their son had great potential and recommended that he should focus full-time on chess. It was a piece of advice they chose to follow. 2016: major tournaments Gukesh featured in the top section of a few open tournaments this year, gaining important experience on the international stage. In January, he was one of 200 players, including more than 20 Grandmasters, who competed in the 2016 Delhi Open. Gukesh outperformed his starting rank of 112 by finishing in 83rd place with 5.5/10. Later the same month, he achieved 6/10 at the Chennai Open. At the Bangkok Chess Club Open in April he scored 4/9. Alongside these tournament appearances, Gukesh was also competing regularly in junior events. These included the Wealth Mumbai Junior Chess Championship where he competed in the U13 section as a nine year-old. With an impressive score of 7/9 he finished fourth. The winner was compatriot Raunak Sadhwani. Six months older than Gukesh, Sadhwani would to go on to become a Grandmaster in 2020. The position shown here is from round 3 where itâs Gukesh, playing White, against Ridit Nimdia: } 
20.c5  Qf6  
21.g4  { A simple pin to win material. } Rad8  
22.gxf5  gxf5  { At the Indian under 11 championship he won 7/11 and finished 18th. That outcome, however, would have been a disappointment given that Gukesh had already made such progress that he had starting rank of number two in the tournament. The following year, in the same U11 Indian championship, he would do much better, as we will discover in the next chapter... }  *


[Event "Masterful Moves: Gukesh"]
