{ 1. Chess in IndiaTo learn more about Gukeshâs career and background, we watched many interviews on YouTube, we listened to podcasts and read articles in magazines and online. As we did so, we determined there were some notable components that contributed to his success. We have compiled these into bite-size Informationals - one per chapter, and this is the first one. By reading them you will discover more about what has made Gukesh the player he has become. Vibrant competitive environment The sheer number of good players, playing against each other in local tournaments with the best progressing to national and international tournaments makes for a highly competitive environment for junior chess in India. As Gukesh told World Chess in an interview in 2023: âThe competition is extremely high and I think thatâs a very healthy thing because it motivates everyone to work harder and to get better at chess.â The players know each other and are often good friends but they do not settle for quick draws when they face each other over the board. They have long been used to needing to beat their compatriots to win local events, and the same attitude pervades their approach when they meet in international tournaments. Gukesh was fortunate to attend the Velammal group of schools which allows chess players to study the game without the need to attend all the regular classes. Other alumni include Adhiban and Praggnanandhaa. Funding for elite junior chess in India Players hoping to reach higher levels can also receive funding from the HelpChess charity run by Sagar Shah. It uses donations to pay for coaching, IT equipment, tournaments and more. Local sponsors are also realising the potential reach that chess can offer them, and they are increasingly funding established and up-and-coming players. Gukesh was first sponsored by Microsense Private Limited, a Chennai company whose managing director happened to be a big chess fan. Success breeds success There has been such success that there is now a regular flow of Indian players attaining new master level titles. Since Vishy Anand became a Grandmaster and inspired a nation to take chess to its heart, an unprecedented number of Indian chess players have achieved norms and titles. Anand was Indiaâs first Grandmaster in 1988; 22 years later, India had 23 Grandmasters, a new one each year on average, but since then it took off, with players having risen through the grassroots system, achieving the GM title at an average of four a year to reach a total of 85 by May 2024. } 
1.--   *


