[Event "Masterful Moves: Gukesh"]
[White "3) Age 10-11. National champion, 2017"]
[Black "2017 Introduction: under-11 winner and first IM norm"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "4r1k1/5ppp/pp1qnb2/8/3P4/PQ2B1P1/1P3PKP/2NR4 b - - 0 22"]

{ FIDE rating January 2017: 2236 }  { FIDE rating December 2017: 2362 }  { FIDE-rated standard-play games: 179 } { In November, with a score of 9/11, Gukesh won the Under-11 Indian championship on tie-break from Pranav, Pranesh and Mendonca } { (now all Grandmasters) } { . The event took place in Pune and featured one of Gukeshâs favourite tactics â played against Prraneeth. This success came after Gukesh finished only 18th at the same tournament last year, despite being second seed. First IM norm However, this year is arguably most notable for Gukesh achieving his first IM norm at the First Friday tournament in Puchong, Malaysia. The tournament was held in October, weeks after he had started training with noted Indian Grandmaster Vishnu Prasanna, a longtime second of Indian GM Adhiban. Gukesh won the tournament comfortably, undefeated with 7/9. Beating a Grandmaster Among the 179 FIDE-rated games he played this year, was his first win against a Grandmaster which came in January. Other tournament successes this year included: First place in the National School } { (U-11 Open) } { Chess Championship, in January, with 9/11 which was 1.5 points ahead of his nearest rival. Gukesh finished 6th at the Bhopal Open in December with 8/10, half a point behind the winner. His wins included a game as White against compatriot Bharat Kumar Reddy Poluri where the key tactic is shown here. } Bxd4  
23.Qc4  {[%cal Bd1d4]} {[%cal Bd4d6]} {[%cal Be3d4]} {[%cal Bc4d4]} {[%csl Rd4]} {[%csl Rd6]} { Rather than taking right away on [d4], Gukesh inserts this intermezzo. The pinned bishop is now attacked three times. } b5  
24.Rxd4  { Queen en prise, no panic - Gukesh calmly chops off the bishop with his rook. } Nxd4  
25.Qxd4  { Gukesh has two pieces for a rook and went to win this game. }  *


[Event "Masterful Moves: Gukesh"]
[White "3) Age 10-11. National champion, 2017"]
[Black "More about Gukesh: 2. Studying classical games"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]

{ Studying classical gamesNot all players do it these days but Gukesh studied classical games and has said he also studied all the world championship matches, with Fischer-Spassky 1972 being his favourite. He uses the ideas from these games in his own play, the double bishop sacrifice against Prraneeth in this chapter, inspired by Lasker-Bauer 1889, is a nice example. If you wonder why even today, coaches still recommend studying great games of the past - this is among the reasons. When ChessBase India visited him at home, Gukesh's bookshelf contained tomes such as: Garry Kasparov on Garry Kasparov: Part III, 1993-2005 and The Soviet Championships by Cafferty and Taiamnov - weighty reading by anyone's standard and full of great classical games from times past. Looking at the material is one thing, recalling it is another but Gukesh is blessed with an excellent memory. When he was very young, Gukesh used to recognise makes of car from just looking at the back of the vehicle and could also easily recall rhymes and cartoons. His father realised what an excellent memory the boy possessed. This reminds us of a young Magnus Carlsen. In the film documentary Magnus } { (2016) } { his father noticed that Magnus would study a book of flags and be able to recall them all, leading to his father to conclude } { (rightly as it turned out) } { that chess might be a good pastime for his son. Magnus, too, studied great games of the past. As he once remarked: 'Contrary to many young colleagues, I do believe that it makes sense to study the classics.' Gukesh went one step further and with his coach Vishnu Prassana also studied Carlsen's games with a particular focus on restricting his opponent. He also studied Veselin Topalov's games to learn about sacrificing material and winning in the ensuing melee. } 
1.--   *


