[Event "Masterful Moves: Gukesh"]
[White "4) Age 11-12. The hunt for norms, 2018"]
[Black "2018 Introduction: chasing the record"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2r3k1/3q3p/1nR1p3/1PQp1ppB/p2P4/P5P1/5P1P/6K1 b - - 0 40"]

{ FIDE rating January 2018: 2354 }  { FIDE rating December 2018: 2466 }  { FIDE-rated standard-play games: 222 } { Gukesh enjoyed outstanding results in two junior tournaments in 2018: Asian Youth and World Cadet champion In April at the Asian Youth Chess Championships, held in Chiangmai, Thailand, he won six medals: five golds for under-12 individual classical } { (8/9) } { , under-12 individual rapid } { (7/7) } { and blitz } { (8.5/9) } { , and under-12 team rapid and blitz; one bronze for team classical. In November he became a world champion by winning the under-12 title section at the World Cadet Championships in Santiago de Compostela, Spain, with 10/11 points. However, his top ambition was to become the worldâs youngest Grandmaster. Record chaser At the start of the year he was just a Candidate Master with one IM norm. Could he gain both the International Master and Grandmaster titles in the same year? If he could do it by December 29 then he would beat the record held by Sergey Karjakin to become the youngest Grandmaster in history. His second IM norm came at the Moscow Open in February where he scored 5/9. The following month he scored 7/9 at the Cappelle la Grande Open which earned him his third norm, securing the International Master title at the age of 11 years, nine months and nine days. Next up: the GM norms He earned his first Grandmaster norm at the Bangkok Open in April with 7/9. Good luck was on the prodigyâs side, as Gukesh beat English Grandmaster Nigel Short simply because Short forgot to press his clock in a superior position. At the Orbis 2 GM event Gukesh scored 7.5/9 points, gaining his second GM norm and 21 rating points. The position here is from the same tournament in his game against compatriot Leon Mendonca. It illustrates Gukeshâs use of an active queen. } Rxc6  
41.bxc6  ( { Capturing with the queen leaves Black slightly better: } 41.Qxc6 Qxc6 42.bxc6 Kf8 43.Kf1 Ke7 44.c7 Kd6 ) Qc7  
42.Be2  {[%cal Be2b5]} {[%csl Bb5]} { Gukesh quickly redeploys his bishop, aiming to get it to the [b5]-square. } g4  
43.Bb5  { Now that the bishop is protecting the c-pawn, Gukesh can activate his queen. It quickly causes chaos in the black defences: } Kf7  
