{ This puzzle is about Gukesh's positional play. What did Black play here and can you guess how play continued? } Bf6  { Although this move is the engine's top choice - Black is aiming to trade the dark squared bishops - there is another practical point to understand. By slowly building up the pressure in this way, Gukesh forces his opponent to make a choice of plans, which may result in a poor decision. } ( { The next two engine favourites, though they lead to no more than a level position, were: } 27...h5 { or } {27...Nd4} ) 
28.Qb6  { White attacks the c-pawn to distract Black from his positional bishop exchange idea, but it is a bad move! In attacking the pawn White abandons the a-file, and Gukesh is able to play flexibly, changing his plan to take full advantage. } ( { Better options for White would have included: } 28.Qa3 { or } {28.Qa1} ) Qa8  { Now the white queen has only one safe square, [a5], but retreating there will be a serious concession. } 
29.Kh2  Bd8  { Now a tactical retreat of the bishop - threatening to net the white queen. } 
30.Qa5  Qxa5  
31.bxa5  Na6  { White resigned - he cannot defend his pawns on the queenside. White's position collapsed in the space of five moves, prompted by the quiet move made by the black bishop. Finnish player Janne Mertanen born 1977 became a FIDE Master in 2007. In 2020, two years after this game was played, six young Indian players including Gukesh had the opportunity to attend group sessions with former world champion Vladimir Kramnik. One of the things he taught them was how to outplay your opponents in equal positions by making practical moves that might induce concessions from them. In a YouTube video by Chessbase India, Gukesh said this was one part of the training that made an impact on him and that he could learn from. On the evidence of this game, he had already started to develop this skill. }  0-1


