[Event "Masterful Moves: Gukesh"]
[White "5) Age 12-13. Gukesh the Grandmaster, 2019"]
[Black "2019 Introduction: the second youngest GM"]
[Result "0-1"]
[FEN "r3r1k1/1b1q1p1p/p5p1/3pb3/R3P3/2PB4/1PQ3PP/R5NK b - - 0 23"]

{ FIDE rating January 2019: 2497 }  { FIDE rating December 2019: 2547 }  { FIDE-rated standard-play games: 188 } { On January 15, 2019, Gukesh became the second-youngest Grandmaster in history at that time by scoring his third GM norm at the 17th Delhi International Grandmaster Open. He was 12 years, 7 months and 17 days old at the time, which means he missed Sergey Karjakinâs record by just 17 days. The record was later broken by Abhimanyu Mishra of the US in 2021 who became a Grandmaster at the age of 12 years, 4 months, 25 days. New In Chess magazine was so impressed by Gukesh's performance that they put him on their front cover of issue number 3, 2019, making him the youngest player to have ever been featured in that way. New In Chess also posed a potentially prophetic question: 'Will he be the next Indian World Champion?' Onwards and upwards Even though he had not set a new record, the title was in the bag and for Gukesh that came as a relief and he was able to put the situation into perspective. âI valued the record a lot, I put myself under so much pressure,' he told World Chess in an interview in 2023 on YouTube. 'That year was very tough, I learned a lot, how to handle pressure and expectations. After, I realised the amount of pressure I put myself under wasnât worth it. There are more things in my career than just the youngest GM record. The year was quite stressful but I learned a lot. For example, when I was trying to break the 2700 barrier the lessons l learned were very helpful.â He also learned from something else that happened in January 2019: the publication of Game Changer, co-authored by Natasha and GM Matthew Sadler. The book details the style of play used by AlphaZero which had become the strongest chess playing engine in the world through the use of artificial intelligence. Looking at Gukesh's games from 2019 onwards we can see he employs AlphaZero style motifs in his play. No surprise then, that when asked by IM Sagar Shah in a ChessBase India interview about his favourite books, Gukesh replied: âI already mentioned it before, I love Game Changer thatâs one of the books I really enjoyed.â Tournament challenge To fulfil his long-term ambition of becoming the best player in the world he needed to continue performing well in strong tournaments, learning how to defeat higher-rated opponents and push up his own rating in the process. Two months after earning the Grandmaster title, Gukesh shared second place in the ninth HD Bank Open in Ho Chi Minh City, Vietnam. He finished with a tournament performance rating of 2700 and 7/9 points. He was a half-point behind winner Wang Hao. In April at the Grenke Open A-section in Karlsruhe, he scored 7.5/9, finishing joint first on points, though fourth equal on tie-break, despite having a starting rank of 42. The position shown here, is from his round 2 game at the Grenke tournament against German Michail Petermann. It shows a number of typical Gukesh tactical traits: sacrifices to open the position, the use of the bishop pair, an exchange sacrifice and an active queen. It is Gukesh, with the black pieces, to play. } Bc6  { Sacrificing the a-pawn to deflect the rook from the fourth rank. } 
24.Rxa6  Rxa6  
25.Rxa6  Bb8  { Now the point of the sacrifice becomes clear: White cannot defend the e-pawn and the centre will be opened. The power of the bishop pair will soon be unleashed. } 
26.e5  Rxe5  
27.Nf3  Re3  
28.Ra1  d4  
29.cxd4  Qd6  { Black activates the queen and threatens to take the knight on [f3] followed by mate on [h2]. } 
30.Ne5  Rxe5  { An exchange sacrifice to clear the centre, the best move in the position. } 
31.dxe5  Qxe5  { The two bishops and the queen make an irresistible force. } 
32.Kg1  Qxh2+  
33.Kf2  Qxg2+  
34.Ke3  Qg3+  
