51.Rg8  Be3  
52.Rf8  f3+  
53.Kh2  g3+  { White resigned. More tournaments In June Gukesh continued his good tournament performances with 7.5/10, half a point behind the joint winners, at the Goa International Open Grandmasters Chess Tournament. At the Grand Swiss in October, held on the Isle of Man, he achieved 6/11 and a performance rating of 2683, finishing 48th compared with a starting rank of 118. A portentous meeting In December at the World Rapid Championship held in Moscow he scored 8.5/15 with a performance rating of 2581. In hindsight it was perhaps most notable for his victory was over Polish player Grzegorz Gajewski, the man who would later become his coach and guide him to success in the 2024 Candidates tournament . }  0-1


[Event "Masterful Moves: Gukesh"]
[White "5) Age 12-13. Gukesh the Grandmaster, 2019"]
[Black "More about Gukesh: 4. No engines..."]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]

{ No engines...When he was younger Gukesh did not use engines to help him with analysing positions. Led by his coach at the time Vishnu Prassana he would look at positions and assess them without switching on the computer. He says this has helped him with his calculation, creativity and ability to find moves as well as improving his trust in his own calculations. Earning rating points on the way up to the highest echelons of chess is typically achieved in open tournaments where winning almost every game is critical to keeping the rating moving upwards. Gukesh developed a style that is based on creating imbalances and reaching complex positions in which he believes he will calculate better than his opponent. His experience of analysing without an engine gives him confidence in his decision-making. His coach Prassana told the New In Chess podcast: âThe decision not to use engines was also about maintaining a particular mindset, thereâs always a certain amount of uncertainty when youâre playing and } { you need to } { be familiar with that feeling and still make a decision.â ...but he did learn how to play like one Although he did not use engines when he was younger, Gukesh did learn all about the play of one particular engine - AlphaZero - by reading the book Game Changer, as we mentioned in the Introduction to this chapter. As you will see in this course, themes from AlphaZeroâs games feature in Gukeshâs play. Of course, not using an engine to analyse positions and thereby build up your own calculation skills and judgment is one thing. His opening preparation these days, like that of all top players, is based heavily on engine recommendations and for Gukesh, at least, on sidelines and alternative moves and positions to find those imbalances he likes to create and to reach positions where he can out-calculate his opponent. } 
1.--   *


