{ How did Gukesh meet Black's 17...[d5] thrust in the centre? } 
18.e5  { Gukesh plays an excellent move that means it is going to be difficult for the black pieces to unwind, and they are not ideal where they are - in particular, the black queen is short of squares, and after the knight moves, the rook on [d8] is needed to defend the [d7] bishop. } ( {(Although it may look tempting to instead play on the long diagonal e.g. by capturing in the centre, Black could then defend with:)} 18.exd5 Nxd5 { when the best White has is } 19.Nf5 Bf6 20.Qh5 Rab8 21.Nd6 g6 22.Qf3 { with only a very small advantage for White. } ) Ne4  ( 18...Ne8 19.h4 Rab8 20.Bd2 Qc5 21.Bb4 Rxb7 22.Bxc5 { and White has won material. } ) 
19.Ne2  {[%cal Be3b6]} {[%csl Bb6]} {[%cal Bb6a5]} {[%cal Bb6d8]} { Another great move, a backwards knight move which could make it harder to spot. It has several threats, including capturing on [e4] which would expose an inadequately defended black bishop on [d7], and it also threatens to land the bishop on [b6] with a fork. } f5  ( 19...Rab8 20.Rxb8 Rxb8 21.Bxe4 { exploiting the undefended bishop on [d7]. } ) 
20.exf6  ( { Also winning are: } 20.Bb6 { and } {20.Bxe4} ) Nxf6  ( { Black can alternatively take with the bishop, but White will still win after: } 20...Bxf6 21.Rxd7 Rxd7 22.Bxe4 ) 
21.Bb6  Qb5  
22.Bxd8  { Black resigned as White will emerge with an extra piece. Eric De Haan is a FIDE Master from the Netherlands. The 12 year-old Gukesh had a good Gibraltar tournament, winning against Grandmasters Iturrizaga and Peralta and gaining over 20 rating points. He lost only two games, to English GMs Adams and Howell. }  1-0


