27.Rec2  Ra7  
28.Ne5  Rac7 $2 ( 28...Ne7 { was important. } 29.Rc5 â©² ) 
29.Nxc6  Bxc6  
{ Can you find the only winning move for White here? } 
30.Qe5 $1 { This move is easy to miss - wrote Sagar Shah in ChessBase. In New In Chess Gukesh added: 'This is the move my opponent had missed when he retreated his rook to [a7]. Black is in a permanent state of paralysis now.' } Qd7  
31.h4  { Black is in a huge Zugzwang: the bishop is pinned, both rooks have to defend the bishop, while the queen is protecting the bishop and the two central pawns on [e6] and [d4]. White wants to be able to take on [c6] in favourable circumstances, and so calmly restrains Black's kingside pawn advances. Meanwhile, Black can do nothing. } ( { Alternatives here were } 31.Bf3 { , } {31.Bh1 , 31.Rc5 , 31.Kf2 , 31.g4} ) Kf7  { Now the queen on [d7] will be lost with a check and hence Gukesh executes the simplifying manoeuvre. } ( { Other tries for Black also fail: } 31...Kh8 32.Kh2 { Getting the king off the back rank. } 32...Kg8 33.Rxc6 Rxc6 34.Qxb5 +- { Black will lose material because capturing the rook on [c1] does not come with check. } ) ( 31...Kf8 32.Qc5+ Ke8 33.Qb6 +- ) ( 31...Qe8 32.Kh2 Qd7 33.Rxc6 Rxc6 34.Qxb5 +- ) 
32.Bxc6  Rxc6  
33.Qxb5  { A nice game by Gukesh.Matthieu Cornette born1985 is a French Grandmaster. }  1-0


