{ Black has just played 48...[Qa3]. Can you find Gukesh's path to victory? } 
49.h6  { Not only softening up Black's king position and opening the g-file, but also giving the white knight access to the dangerous [h5] square. In Game Changer GM Matthew Sadler and I noted AlphaZero's tendency to push its h-pawn to create damage, and also that it would often move pieces out of the way and even sacrifice material in order to get its knights to the right squares. This game was played just a few months after the publication of Game Changer - it looks like Gukesh had already adopted some of its ideas into his own games. } ( { Another possible path to consider is } 49.Ne2 { which unblocks the g-file and so immobilises the Black bishop on [e7], as it needs to stay put so that [g7] doesn't cave in. White would then plan to follow up with pushing the a-pawn. } ) ( 49.a7 { immediately is not good as it would be met by } 49...Bc5 ) gxh6  
50.Nh5  { The start of a wonderful knight tour by Gukesh. Starting from [g3], the knight heads to [h5]-[f4]-[d5] before finally sacrificing itself on [c7]. By moving the knight to [h5], White is also immobilising the bishop on [e7]. White plans to advance the a-pawn next and Black will not have the move ...[Bc5] as a defence. } e4  { A deflection tactic. White needs to take the e-pawn to avoid Black's perpetual check starting with ...[Qf3]+, and so Black will be able to remove White's intimidating a-pawn. } 
51.Qxe4  Qxa6  
52.Nf4  Ke8  
53.Ne6  ( { It is also very strong for White to continue his knight's tour with } 53.Nd5 { at which point Black's best is to take it, sacrificing the exchange. } ) Rc8  
54.Rg8+  Kd7  
55.Qd5+  Bd6  
56.Rg7+  Ke8  
57.Nc7+  {[%csl Gg3]} {[%csl Gh5]} {[%cal Gg3h5]} {[%cal Gh5f4]} {[%csl Gf4]} {[%cal Gf4e6]} {[%csl Ge6]} {[%cal Ge6c7]} {[%csl Gc7]} {[%cal Bc7e8]} {[%csl Re8]} { After a tour that began on [g3] the knight gives itself up on [c7] to help White deliver checkmate. } Rxc7  
58.Qe6+  { Bjorn Ahlander born 1963, of Sweden, is an International Master as well as a National Arbiter and FIDE Instructor. This game was played at the Grenke Open 2019 A-section where Gukesh, with a starting rank of 42, was one of eight players who finished on 7.5/9. Tie-breaks ranked him joint fourth. }  1-0


[Event "Masterful Moves: Gukesh"]
[White "6) Age 13-14. Online chess, 2020"]
[Black "2020 Introduction: chess goes online"]
[Result "0-1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]

{ FIDE rating January 2020: 2542 }  { FIDE rating December 2020: 2563 }  { FIDE-rated standard-play games: 28 } { After scoring 6/10 at the Gibraltar International Masters in January, Gukesh achieved two tournament victories. Wins over the board... His first came in February at an event to celebrate the 110th anniversary of the HillerÃ¸d Chess Club in Denmark. Starting as the second seed, Gukesh scored 8/9 points and edged out the top-seeded Chinese Grandmaster Zeng Chongsheng by half a point. A week later, Gukesh scored 7.5/9 at the Cannes Chess Festival 2020. He was undefeated and took first place, achieving a performance rating of 2667. He again finished a half-point ahead of Zeng Chongsheng who scored 7 along with French International Master Guillaume Lamard. His over the board progress was halted by the outbreak of the Covid pandemic. From March to the end of the year he played no more FIDE-rated standard-play games. ...and then online Instead, the focus switched to online chess. Gukesh notched up a notable success at the end of the year when he won the FIDE online World Cadets & Youth Rapid Chess Championships Under-14 section by defeating Volodar Murzin in an Armageddon play-off. Here we show the full game from a Titled Tuesday encounter in April with US Grandmaster and popular commentator Robert Hess. Titled Tuesday is Chess.com's weekly 11-round Swiss tournament for titled players, occurring twice each Tuesday since February 1, 2022 at 8am PT/17:00 CET and 2pm PT/23:00 CET. Titled Tuesday debuted on December 30, 2014 as a monthly nine-round event. It became a weekly tournament on April 7, 2020 and permanently expanded to its current length of 11 rounds on October 20, 2020. Before the Covid pandemic it attracted about 400 titled players to each event, once lockdowns began participation peaked at over 1,000. On the day of this game took place there were 1,037 players, according to titledtuesday.com. Robert Hess - Gukesh Dommaraju, online, April 21, 2020. } 
1.b3  e5  
2.Bb2  d6  
3.e3  g6  
4.Ne2  Bg7  
5.d3  Ne7  
6.Nd2  { White is playing a line that starts quietly. Many players steer away from their main openings in Titled Tuesday and use it as a chance to experiment in a strong field without assisting future Over-The-Board opponents to know their openings! } O-O  
7.g3  Nbc6  
8.Bg2  Be6  { Black has already equalised against White's modest set-up. } 
9.h4  h6  
10.d4  d5  
11.Nf3  e4  { Here Gukesh elects to close the centre. He has a space advantage and is preparing to launch forward his kingside pawns, and a closed centre allows Black to do this with safety. } 
12.Nd2  Bg4  
13.Bh3  ( { White gives up his right to castle kingside in view of Black's potential to expand there. If instead } 13.Nf1 a5 { Black would still play on both sides of the board, with his advance of the rook's pawn. } ) Bxh3  
14.Rxh3  Qd7  { Gukesh plays direct developing moves, and this one comes with a tempo. } 
15.Nf4  Nd8  
16.Ba3  Ne6  { Gukesh offers the exchange of White's most active piece. This is a technique that AlphaZero used regularly, White's remaining pieces, especially the queen, rooks and [d2]-knight are rather hampered in their movement by the white pawns and Black's central pawn structure. } 
17.Qg4  { The white queen aims for activity... } f5  ( { Gukesh immediate bats back the white queen, a strategy he continues throughout this game. There was a better tactical choice available to Black here, which would have been: } 17...h5 18.Nxh5 gxh5 19.Qxh5 c5 -+ { - White could not simply retreat the queen in this line because the rook on [h3] would be loose after the exchange of knights on [f4]. } ) 
18.Qe2  { White is looking to play against Black's loosely defended [g6]-pawn. } Kh7  
19.h5  g5  
20.Bxe7  { Robert Hess plays an intermediate move removing the defender of [g6]... but Gukesh meets it with... } gxf4  { First one Zwischenantwort an intermediate move in response to an intermediate move... } 
21.Bxf8  f3  { ...And then another! A nice Zwischenzug, attacking the queen and establishing a strong pawn on [f3] before recapturing on [f8]. Notice how the white queen's mobility is still severely restricted and its only option is to retreat. } 
22.Qf1  Rxf8  
23.Rh1  { For the last couple of moves, the engine has been wanting White to sacrifice his knight on [f3] just to gain some more mobility. Despite Black's apparent material deficit of an exchange, and no immediate attack on the horizon, the evaluation is winning for Gukesh as White's pieces cannot get moving. This must have been a frustrating game to play for Hess! } c5  { The best move. Black will be able to get a rook to the open c-file first. } 
24.c3  cxd4  
25.cxd4  Rc8  { Black gets to the c-file first and still the white queen can't get active. } 
26.a4  Qc6  
27.Rd1  Qc2  ( 27...Qc3 { is even stronger. Gukesh has a very active queen, whereas White's pieces are still all very tied up. This will allow Gukesh to take his time improving his position. } ) 
28.Qh3  Rf8  { Constraint first - defending [f5]. } 
29.Rg1  Ng5  
30.Qf1  a6  { The white queen has no squares! - and nor does the king! } 
31.Rh1  Rc8  
32.Rh4  Qb2  
33.g4  Rc1  { Forcing mate in a few moves as the white king has nowhere to go. } 
34.gxf5  Qc2   0-1


[Event "Masterful Moves: Gukesh"]
[White "6) Age 13-14. Online chess, 2020"]
[Black "More about Gukesh: 5. The Sagar Shah effect"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]

{ The Sagar Shah effectInternational Master Sagar Shah founded ChessBase India in 2015 with his wife Amruta Mokal. Their online service covers news about all the Indian players - both the established stars and the upcoming next generation - showcasing their games and their achievements. Whenever an Indian player attains a new title which these days seem like every other week, you can be sure Shah and his team will write about it in an online news post. If an Indian player wins - or does well in - a tournament, Shah will interview them. He gets access to the players and also to the top tournaments, providing a special viewpoint from all the key events. Motivation The Indian youngsters grow up reading and watching this content and feel motivated to play their best chess and improve so that they will appear on the website and YouTube channel. Gukeshâs father Rajinikanth recognised this in an interview with Shah in 2017 when he said to Shah: âThe way you are covering tournaments, itâs a boost, they are getting impressed by these things, not only Gukesh but for all kids, whenever there is an article the kid gets pumped up for the next match.â âI have seen Praggnanandhaa and Nihal Sarin doing wonders after being extensively covered. In our age category, the 2006 kids i.e. those born in the year 2006 like Gukesh, are super competitive. You name any kid, theyâve all been covered, not one is left out.â âThey are all impressed by that, and I can vouch for it, Gukesh looks for ChessBase India news every day. It motivates them. He wants to give his best so that his game will be covered in the next report.â } 
1.--   *


