[FEN "3r1qk1/p4p1p/5npP/np1pNP2/3P4/1P2QP2/PK1N4/2R5 b - - 0 27"]

{ FIDE rating January 2021: 2563 }  { FIDE rating December 2021: 2641 }  { FIDE-rated standard-play games: 114 } { This year featured a mix of online tournaments interspersed with over the board events, sometimes with players wearing face masks, as lockdown rules changed around the world. On the rise again After 12 months of no over the board FIDE-rated games, Gukesh was able to regain his momentum in face-to-face competition, increasing his rating by almost 80 points by December. In August, for example, he finished second at the Terras de TrÃ¡s-os-Montes Open in Portugal with 8/9 and a performance rating of 2747. His only defeat was to compatriot and tournament winner Arjun Erigaisi who scored 8.5/9. The position shown here is from round 3 of this tournament with Gukesh playing White against Aspet Tadevosyan of Spain. } Rc8  { How should White continue here? } 
28.fxg6  hxg6  
29.Nxg6  fxg6  
30.Qe6+  {[%cal Be6g8]} {[%cal Be6c8]} {[%csl Rc8]} {[%csl Rg8]} { A fork, the rook on [c8] will fall. } Kh7  
31.Rxc8  Qxc8  
32.Qxc8  { Black resigned. Gukesh also achieved an admirable 9th place at the World Rapid Championships in Warsaw with a performance rating of 2753. In the World Blitz Championship immediately after, he had a starting rank of 119 and finished 32nd with 12.5/21. The highs and the lows However, it is worth pointing out that although these are some of the highlights, not every tournament yields a positive score or increase in rating - even for a top prodigy. Players trying to climb up the rankings and competing in many events, particularly open tournaments, inevitably encounter plenty of occasions when things do not go their way. In 2021, for example, Gukesh scored 5/11 at FIDE Grand Swiss in Riga; he reached only the second round at the World Cup in Sochi; and at the Yerevan Open his score of 6/9 lost him 6.9 rating points because he was the number two seed. The ability to take such results in oneâs stride, focus on chess improvement and come back stronger at the next event is a necessary part of the journey to reaching the elite level of world chess. Resilience has certainly been a key factor in Gukeshâs long-term success. }  *


[Event "Masterful Moves: Gukesh"]
[White "7) Age 14-15. Over the internet & over the board, 2021"]
[Black "More about Gukesh: 6. Resilience and mindset"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]

{ Resilience and mindsetIn the journey to the top of elite chess, some tournaments will not go well and rating points will be lost along the way. Some crucial games will end in defeat. Gukesh has recognised this and has deliberately set out to teach himself to cope with adversity and bounce back quickly. Keeping calm, and doing yoga which he practises almost every day, has been key. As he told World Chess in 2023: âWhen I was younger, maybe a few years back, I used to be so emotional, I used to get angry a lot and I was just very short-tempered. Once I started to focus on my mental fitness as well, just doing some meditation, some yoga, and stuff like that, it really helped me calm down. âA few years back, it took me like the whole tournament to forget about the loss; it now takes me around like half an hour, one hour, to get into the right state of mind, so I am able to recover quickly. Even after winning, I donât get too excited! One of the tricks I followed was that irrespective of the result, I just start thinking about what I am going to do in the next game.â The most recent and most notable example came in the 2024 Candidates tournament when, under time pressure, he lost to Alireza Firouzja in round 7 and his bid to win the tournament appeared in jeopardy. The following day was a rest day and Gukesh used it to refocus on the task ahead. âThe moment when I thought I was at my absolute best and things can go really well was the rest day after the loss against Alireza,â he explained to FIDE Chess. âI was upset for a while but I felt really good physically, mentally and chess-wise - so I felt very sharp. After that I was pretty confident that I have a lot of chancesâ¦something fired me up.â And so it proved, in the second half of the tournament Gukesh achieved three wins } { (against Vidit, Abasov and Firouzja) } { and four draws which gave him victory by half a point. Courage and calmness The other attribute often mentioned in relation to Gukesh's mindset is that he appears to possess 'nerves of steel' due to how he takes so many brave decisions at the board. We cover this in the Gukesh Style chapter by looking at, among other things, how he leaves his king seemingly at the mercy of his opponentâs pieces while he coolly conducts an attack at the other end of the board that lands just in time. âThe second seed Gukesh, time and again, has shown that he possesses nerves of steel,â wrote Chessbase India in 2016 as nine year-old Gukesh vied for the National Under-11 Championship. Eight years later, âIncredible stamina and nerves of steel,â was the headline of an article in American Chess Magazine reporting on Gukeshâs success at the Candidates. Just play through some of his games for yourself and you'll see it too. There are more than 150 to choose from in this course. } 
1.--   *


