{ White has just played 41. [Ra6] attacking the knight on [b6], and hoping to open a path to the black king across the 6th rank. The problem is that Gukesh Dommaraju is playing Black, and he is not going to oblige. What followed? } Qb7  { This is one of our favourite Gukesh sequences because it contains so many characteristic elements. First, Black moves his queen to the long diagonal, a forcing move that attacks White's rook. Gukesh isn't scared to move defences away from his own king, provided that the opponent doesn't have a concrete way in. Keep an eye on the black knight on [e4]. It is blockading White's e-pawn, and also blocking the white queen's entry into the game, however also currently blocking the black queen. } 
42.Qf1  ( { The engine's choice is to already sacrifice White's rook, but it is hopeless as even so, the black queen can enter the position via the b-file, and the knight on e4 still blocks the white queen. } 42.Rxb6 Qxb6 ) Ng3  { The knight temporarily leaves its spot to attack the enemy queen, and let its own queen into the position down the long diagonal. } 
43.Qd3  { White continues to defend the rook and dreams of entering on [g6]. } Qh1+  { The queen comes in. The knight on [b6] is left blocking the white rook unguarded as Black unleashes a series of forcing moves. } 
44.Kf2  Ne4+  { And back to base for the knight, checking the white king, and blocking the white queen. } 
45.Ke2  Qg2+  
46.Ke1  c2 $1 { Now another Gukesh speciality - the far advanced pawn. The c-pawn threatens to queen in some lines, and also has another important job. } 
47.Qb3+  Kh8  
48.Qf7  { The white queen finally gets close to the action but it is too late. } Qg1+  
49.Ke2  ( 49.Qf1 Qxe3+ 50.Qe2 Qg3+ 51.Kf1 Rf8+ { also leads to checkmate. } ) Qd1  { Gukesh has accurately calculated the mating sequence. The queen is defended by the far advanced c-pawn. Armenian Artur Davtyan became an IM in 2019. }  0-1


