[Event "Masterful Moves: Gukesh"]
[White "8) Age 15-16. Olympiad gold, 2022"]
[Black "Introduction: gold at the Olympiad and a 2700+ rating"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2bq1bk1/5r2/2p1pp2/r4npp/N1QPR3/P4N1P/5PPB/1R4K1 w - - 0 31"]

{ FIDE rating January 2022: 2614 }  { FIDE rating December 2022: 2725 }  { FIDE-rated standard-play games: 127 }  { Gukesh achieved two landmark successes in 2022 that placed him firmly among the worldâs chess elite. Glory at the Olympiad In August at the age of 16 he won the individual gold medal on board one at the Olympiad in Chennai. He finished with 9/11 having won his first eight games in a row including victories over Alexei Shirov and Fabiano Caruana. Behind him were Nodirbek Abdusattorov, 8.5/11, silver medal, and Magnus Carlsen, 7.5/9, bronze medal. His team finished third overall, giving him a bronze medal as well. It was all the more impressive that his team - India 2 } { (Gukesh, Sarin, Praggnanandhaa, Adhiban, Sadhwani) } { - had a starting rank of 11 and was not even considered the best team that his country entered into the competition. The Indian first team had a starting rank of two but finished in fourth place. Here is the crucial position from the Olympiad game where Gukesh defeats Caruana with the black pieces. The American, White to play, moves his knight towards the centre but has overlooked a strong reply: } 
31.Nc5  Qd5  { Gukesh brings his queen to the most active square. Black now has three pieces attacking the knight on [c5], which is currently the only defender of the rook on [e4]. Caruana's position soon collapses and Gukesh finishes it off with a nice mating threat: } 
32.Qe2  Rxa3  
33.Rd1  Rfa7  
34.g4  hxg4  
35.hxg4  Nh6  
36.Bg3  e5  
37.Nxe5  fxe5  
38.Rxe5  Bxg4  
39.Qd2  Qf3  
40.Rxg5+  Rg7  
41.Re1  Bh3  {[%cal Bf3g2]} {[%csl Bg2]} { Threatening mate in one. } 
42.Bd6  Bxd6  
43.Rxg7+  Kxg7  
44.Qg5+  Kh7  
45.Ne4  Qxe4  { Caruana resigned. If he captures the queen Gukesh will deliver mate on the back rank. Speaking to New In Chess about his success at the Olympiad where he simply kept on winning game after game, Gukesh explained that legendary US Grandmaster Gata Kamsky had inspired him after a tournament in Biel earlier in the year when he told Gukesh that he believed that the youngster had stopped playing in his usual style halfway through the event and consequently lost the tournament. 'Kamsky told me you play like yourself no matter what the tournament standings are. You should just try to win because that's who you are. It really helped at the Olympiad. I got three wins and then kept playing for a win, four, five, six, seven and even after the eighth win against Fabi.' Breaking the 2700 barrier Gukeshâs results at the Olympiad came with a stunning performance rating of 2867 and when the new ratings for September were published he had surpassed the 2700 threshold to hit a new high of 2726. He was no longer just one of a number of very strong young Indian grandmasters, he had joined the super-Grandmaster level. }  *


[Event "Masterful Moves: Gukesh"]
[White "8) Age 15-16. Olympiad gold, 2022"]
[Black "More about Gukesh: 7. Coaching"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]

{ CoachingGukesh has benefited from good coaching throughout his career. After local teachers in his earliest years, he worked with: Karthikeyan Pandian, a coach who at the time was an International Master, he later attained the Grandmaster title in 2019 - the same year that Gukesh became GM. Grandmaster Vishnu Prasanna worked with Gukesh between the ages of 10-15. Much of the training focused on decision-making, mindset and calculation } { (sometimes spending 3-4 hours on one position, as he told the New In Chess podcast) } { . In particular, when studying positions they decided not to use an engine and instead Gukesh had to work it out for himself. Gukesh was also one of the first five players to receive a fellowship to the Westbridge Anand Chess Academy } { (WACA) } { in 2020 } { (the others were Nihal Sarin, Raunak Sadhwani, Rameshbabu Praggnanandhaa and his elder sister Vaishali) } { . The academy is funded by Westbridge Capital, an investment firm, with Anand mentoring the players along with top coaches such as Artur Yusupov, Sandipan Chanda and Grzegorz Gajewski } { (the latter becoming Gukeshâs trainer two years later) } { . You may be familiar with the âWACAâ logo - it can often be seen on Gukeshâs jacket. Gukesh also had intensive coaching sessions with former world champion Vladimir Kramnik in 2019 and 2020 with other elite Indian juniors. Polish Grandmaster Grzegorz Gajewski, who previously had been a second to Vishy Anand, has been Gukeshâs trainer since late 2022 - an appointment Anand had helped Gukesh to make. Gajewski's first assignment was to help with the opening preparation for the Tata Steel Masters 2023 tournament. 'I was really interested in working with him,' Gukesh told New In Chess in 2024. 'Our collaboration started and it has been beautiful.' For the Candidates and World Championship tournaments there is also a small team working on preparation for Gukesh overseen by Gajewski. Players do not typically reveal who is in their preparation team until the tournament is over, although it has been revealed that Paddy Upton is part of team Gukesh. For the past few months he has been helping Gukesh with mental conditioning. Upton has previously worked with the Indian cricket and hockey teams, among many others. } 
1.--   *


