32.Rf4  {[%cal Bf4c4]} {[%csl Bc4]} { Gukesh harnesses the attacking power of queen and rook combined, a lethal force against the black king. The trick is to find a good avenue of attack. In this position, Gukesh chose the 4th rank where the rook will be able to get across to the c-file. It can be hard to spot because the rook has to first of all drop backwards. Remember that - rather like airplane emergency exits - attacking lines can also be behind you! } Rb8  { Not the best move but there is no safety for Black. } ( { A sterner try would have been: } 32...Qd7 33.Rc4+ Kb7 34.Rxb4+ Kc8 35.Qb6 { Black is extremely tied down, and has an open king. Play could continue: } 35...Qc6 36.Qd4 Qe6 37.Qc5+ Bc6 38.Rh4 h6 39.Qb6 Rb8 40.Qxa6+ { and White's attack continues, with the knowledge that White now has five pawns for the bishop! } ) 
33.Rc4+  Kb7  
34.Rxb4  { With the queen about to be lost for a rook, Black resigned. This tournament was the second of three classical FIDE rated tournaments that Gukesh played in April 2022 - in fact, he clocked up an incredible 27 classical FIDE-rated games plus 11 rapid games, all in a 30-day month! Daniel Romero Pallares born 1988 of Spain achieved his FIDE Master title in the same year this game was played: 2022. }  1-0


