17.Ng5  { This move reminds me of an AlphaZero style attack. Gukesh has carefully set up the elements, in particular a closed centre with his pawns on [d4] and [e5], and Black's pawns on [e6] and [d5]. The bishops are pointing at the castled king, and AlphaZero liked to put a knight on [g5] in the vicinity of Black's king, supported by a pawn on [h4]. If Black were later to defend with ...[g6] then the h-pawn is in place to advance to [h5], continuing the attack. } Bxg5  ( { After } 17...h6 { White has a pleasant choice of employing a bouncing bishop manoeuvre to highlight the weakness of the squares around the black king or entering with the knight. } {(18.Bh7+ Kh8 19.Bb1 Bxg5 20.hxg5 g6 21.Qf3 with a strong attack. )} 18.Nh7 Rfd8 19.Qg4 Kh8 20.Ng5 Bxg5 21.hxg5 { and Black is in trouble. } ) 
