55.Kg6  ( 55.Rg7 gxh4 56.Rg6+ Kd5 { The black king comes over to assist with stopping the pawns on the queenside. So far, White has not been able to capture on [h4] due to knight forks. } 57.Rg5+ {(57.Kxh4 Rxa7 and Black will continue with ...[f3] next. )} 57...Kc6 58.Kg4 Rxa7 59.Rg6+ Kb5 60.Kxf4 Rh7 { Black rounds up the b-pawn and then comes back across to the kingside } ) Nf3  { The only winning move. It defends the g pawn and threatens a fork on [e5]. Alternatives give no more than equality. } ( { For example } 55...f3 56.b5 Nxb5 57.Rxf3 gxh4 58.Re3+ Kd5 59.Rh3 { when White will need to defend R+N v R but should be able to. } ) 
56.Rf6+  Kd5  ( { Not } 56...Ke5 57.Rf5+ Kd6 58.Ra5 { wins for White! } ) 
57.Rf5+  Ne5+  
58.Kxg5  f3  
59.Kf4  Kd4 $1 ( 59...f2 60.a8=Q+ Rxa8 61.Kg3 { should lead to a draw. } ) 
60.Rf8  ( 60.Rxe5 f2 ) ( 60.Rf6 f2 61.Kg3 Nd3 62.h5 Rxa7 63.h6 Ke5 64.Rf3 Rh7 { Again Black can afford to stop the opposing pawns - White cannot capture the knight because Black would queen. } ) Ng6+  ( { White resigned. Also winning are } 60...f2 { and } {60...Nd3+ (Dey Mahitosh born 2005 gained his FIDE Master title in 2019. Gukesh was undefeated in this tournament, the Reykjavik Open, up to the final round, when he played Praggnanandhaa and lost, which gave Praggnanandhaa clear first.)} )  0-1


[Event "Masterful Moves: Gukesh"]
[White "9) Age 16-17. Candidates qualification, 2023"]
[Black "2023 Introduction: Gukesh reaches the Candidates"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1bb1r1k1/p3qp2/1pp3p1/6r1/PP1Pp2p/4P2P/1BRQ1PP1/2R2N1K w - - 0 30"]

{ FIDE rating January 2023: 2725 }  { FIDE rating December 2023: 2720 }  { FIDE-rated standard-play games: 120 } { Gukesh's strong junior career continued in 2023 with a victory in the Junior Speed Chess Championship in June. In August, he crossed the 2750 FIDE rating barrier, the youngest player ever to do so. The following month his rating surpassed that of Vishy Anand. It was the first time in 37 years that Anand was not India's number one player. However, his year was centred around attempting to qualify for the Candidates â not an easy task. Gukesh got to the quarter-final of the World Cup in August but needed to reach the semi-final to achieve qualification. He did not fare so well at the Grand Swiss, finishing with 5/11 while compatriot Vidit came first with 8.5/11. And his rating, while impressive, was behind that of Alireza Firouzja who pursued the best rating qualification slot by playing in some hastily-arranged tournaments late on in the year, thereby overtaking Wesley So. FIDE Circuit That left one more option for Gukesh: the FIDE Circuit. This was a complicated arrangement but it boiled down to performing well in five FIDE-approved tournaments during the year. Each of a playerâs top five performances were awarded Circuit points, according to a complex formula based on the results achieved and the strength of the tournament, and the player with the highest total points would qualify. Fortunately for Gukesh, the highest-scoring player on the Circuit was Fabiano Caruana who had already qualified for the Candidates by finishing third at the World Cup. Therefore, whoever finished second on the Circuit would take its qualification slot. Gukesh had four strong tournament performances: joint runner-up at the WR Masters in Dusseldorf, third at the Sharjah Masters, third at Norway Chess classical in Stavanger, quarter-finalist at the World Cup in Baku. He needed one more tournament success to overtake Dutchman Anish Giri, who among other achievements had won both the Tata Steel Masters and the Dutch national championship in 2023. Giriâs seventh place at the Grand Swiss in November, earning more precious Circuit points, gave Gukesh little time to respond. From December 1-10 he played in the London Chess Classic but his third place did not net him enough Circuit points. He also participated in the Pro-Biz tournament the next day where he partnered DeepMind CEO Demis Hassabis, the man behind the AlphaZero project, in a game against French GM Jules Moussard and Natasha - you can find out more about that in the related puzzle in this chapter. How could Gukesh get the Circuit points he needed with such little time remaining? An eight-player tournament called the Chennai Masters was quickly arranged for December 15-21. It was not an easy field to face with players such as Levon Aronian and Parham Maghsoodloo participating. Also playing was Arjun Erigaisi who had a slim chance of outscoring Gukesh and Giri in Circuit points if results went his way. This tournament would take Gukesh's total number of FIDE-rated standard-play games for the year to 120. Going into the final round he was half a point ahead of his rival. Erigaisi won his game but Gukesh did just enough, getting a draw against Pentala Harikrishna to win the title on tie-break from Erigaisi. That tournament victory gave Gukesh sufficient points to edge out Giri and take the coveted qualification slot for the Candidates. What an end to the year! Well, not quite. Gukesh then decided to play in the World Rapid and Blitz in Samarkand, Uzbekistan from December 26-30. Both tournaments were won by Magnus Carlsen. Gukesh finished 25th in the rapid and 32nd in the blitz, just below his starting rank in each one. The position shown here is from Gukesh's final game of 2023, on December 30. It is round 21 of the World Blitz Championship and he is playing Black against Manuel Petrosyan of Armenia. It is a typical Gukesh set-up with both an advanced e-pawn cutting his opponent's position in two and an Alpha Zero-style advanced h-pawn which had prompted his opponent, White to move, to put his own pawn on [h3], weakening his king's defences. The game continued as follows: } 
30.d5  Bxh3  { Gukesh decides to go for it with a bishop sacrifice. } ( { The engine prefers this move } 30...Rxd5 { but it's a blitz game and with time ticking away, White may not be able to defend correctly against Gukesh's onslaught. } ) 
31.gxh3  Qd7  
32.f4  exf3  {[%cal Bf3g2]} {[%csl Bg2]} {[%cal Bf3e2]} {[%csl Be2]} { The black pawn has reached the sixth rank where it will help to trap the white king. } 
33.Qd4  { threatening mate in one, but Gukesh has other ideas. } Qxh3+  
34.Rh2  { It is now mate in four. } Rg1+ $1 
35.Kxg1  Bxh2+  { White resigned. It's mate in two. } 
36.Kf2  Qg2+  
37.Ke1  Qe2  { Now that really was the end of Gukeshâs chess year. As far as we know, he didnât begin another tournament on December 31! }  *


[Event "Masterful Moves: Gukesh"]
[White "9) Age 16-17. Candidates qualification, 2023"]
[Black "More about Gukesh: 8. Role models and parental support"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]

{ Role modelsRameshbabu Praggnanandhaa was an early inspiration for Gukesh. A year older than Gukesh and also from Chennai, he enjoyed success early on as a junior, winning the World Youth Chess Championship Under-8 title in 2013 with a perfect score of 11/11 and the Under-10 title two years later. Pragg's success as a junior was an inspiration to Gukesh } { (whose father told ChessBase India in an interview that his son followed Praggâs games closely) } { . Vishy Anand was, unsurprisingly, Gukeshâs role model. India's first Grandmaster, who became world champion in 2007, has been an inspiration for almost every Indian chess player since and Gukesh is no exception. âWhen I was starting out in chess it was only Vishy Anand sir for me,â he told World Chess in 2023 } { (using the respectful Indian way of referring to seniors as âsirâ) } { . âIf I have to say who is my role model, as a chess player and as a person, I would say always Vishy sir.â Gukesh still takes advice from Anand, speaking to him before the Candidates tournament in 2024, for example. Parental support Gukeshâs parents have supported their son on his journey to the top of world chess after Gukesh himself had chosen this path. His father has accompanied him to tournaments around the world, putting on hold his own career as a surgeon while Gukeshâs mother was working as a microbiologist. At one point 70% of their income was being spent on Gukeshâs chess activities. Travelling to international tournaments is not cheap, it is only the super elite who make money from playing chess. At the most financially difficult times friends and family also contributed to help fund the prodigyâs development. These days, of course, things are easier for Gukesh and his family when it comes to finances. He wins prize money and has sponsors. However, his parents help him keep his feet on the ground. As he told New In Chess: "My mom has always told me, 'I will be extremely happy when people say Gukesh is a great chess player but I'll be even happier when they say he is an even better human being. That is something my parents have been very particular about, being polite and humble. My parents always told me I should be like Vishy Sir." } 
1.--   *


