30.e5  { Gukesh continues forwards opening lines. This move is the engine's top choice, and it relies on White being comfortable that his attack will land first. } Rb2 $2 { A mistake from Praggnanandhaa, who must have missed Gukesh's pretty next move. } ( 30...Qg2+ 31.Ke2 g6 { blocks the diagonal but there is still the question of the weak back rank, with [Ne7]+ threatened resulting in a complex position that the engine assesses as good for White. Play could continue: } 32.f6 Qg4+ {(32...Rb8 leads to favourable exchanges for White after 33.Qe4)} 33.f3 Qg2+ 34.Kd1 Qxf3+ 35.Qxf3 Nxf3 36.Re2 { and the tactics are not over yet: } 36...Rd7 37.Bb3 g5 38.e6 fxe6 39.Rxe6 Kf7 40.Ra6 g4 41.Kc2 Kg6 42.f7+ Kxf7 43.Nf6+ { picking up the rook. } ) 
31.Ne7+  { Another sacrificial tactic from Gukesh that opens up lines of attack - the queen to [d8] if the knight is not captured, and allowing the pawn to advance to [f6] with tempo if the queen takes the knight. } Qxe7  ( 31...Kf8 { allows mate in one with } 32.Qd8 ) 
32.f6  { Black resigned here. Moving the queen or taking on [f6] allows a quick mate, for example: } gxf6  
33.Qxh7+  Kf8  
34.Qh8  { This victory helped Gukesh finish top joint in the WR Masters. Although he lost the tie-break to Levon Aronian, his success brought him plenty of FIDE Circuit points to help him qualify for the Candidates. Gukesh and Praggnanandhaa are no strangers to each other's game and they don't take quick draws. According to my database including blitz games they played each other eight times between December 2022 and September 2023 - and White won every single game Gukesh was White six times and Praggnanandha twice! }  1-0


