[Event "Masterful Moves: Gukesh"]
[White "10) Age 17-18. Road to the World Championship, 2024 "]
[Black "2024 Introduction: winning the Candidates."]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2b5/2P4p/5k2/3rN3/8/3N2P1/4K3/2Rn4 b - - 0 1"]

{ FIDE rating January 2024: 2725 }  { FIDE rating September 2024: 2764 }  { FIDE-rated standard-play games: 57 } { In April 2024 Gukesh made headlines around the world when, still only 17, he became the youngest player to win the Candidates tournament. Now age 18, he will be the youngest World Championship contender when he faces Ding Liren in Singapore in November. The year had started brightly for Gukesh when he finished joint top at the Tata Steel Masters in Wijk aan Zee in a four-way tie. In the play-offs he defeated the home favourite Anish Giri but was disappointed to just miss out on the tournament title when he lost to Wei Yi. Gukesh then competed in the Freestyle Chess G.O.A.T Challenge, a chess 960 tournament, in February. The endgame position in the diagram is from his win over Magnus Carlsen in the round robin stage. It looks like it could be from a regular chess game rather than a chess 960 - sometimes called Fischer random - encounter. We chose it because it illustrates the Gukesh-Style-Factor of co-ordinated knights. Gukesh, playing White, has to find five consecutive only moves - other choices would have been, at best, drawing - and then he uses the pair of knights to bring the game to a swift conclusion. } Nb2  
2.Rf1+  Ke7  
3.Nc6+  Kd6  
4.Rf6+  Kxc7  
5.Nxb2  Bb7  
6.Nb4  Rh5  
{ Now watch how Gukesh uses those knights: } 
7.Nc4  Rh3  
8.Rf7+  {[%csl Rb6]} {[%csl Rc6]} {[%csl Rd6]} {[%cal Bb4c6]} {[%cal Bc4b6]} {[%cal Bc4d6]} Kb8  
9.Nd6  Bh1  
10.Na6+  Ka8  
11.Nb5  { The game ended here. White threatens to mate in 1. The next few moves could have been: } Bb7  
12.Rf8+  Bc8  { With a winning endgame for White. This chess 960 event, held in a luxury resort in Germany, perhaps provided some welcome relief from the roster of regular tournaments before Gukesh got ready to head off to Toronto to play in the Candidates in April. Candidates 2024 His approach at the Candidates was to play solidly against the three most experienced players } { (he achieved draws as Black and White against Caruana, Nakamura and Nepomniachtchi) } { while he looked for more ambitious options against the other four. He got a win and a draw against both Vidit and Praggnanandhaa; he lost to Firouzja when in time trouble but bounced back to beat the same player in the penultimate round; and, crucially, he also scored a maximum 2/2 against Nijat Abasov, the tournamentâs lowest rated player. That approach brought him a score of 9/14 which was enough to win the Candidates by half a point, a stunning achievement from a player who almost nobody had considered to be among the favourites. Adulation and extensive media coverage inevitably followed. Could Gukesh become the youngest world chess champion ever? Unruffled, Gukesh then played in the Grand Chess Tour events between May and August such as the Superbet Chess Classic in Romania where he was joint runner-up behind Fabiano Caruana. He also played in the Sinquefield Cup in St Louis where one of his games was against the man he was set to face three months later: world champion Ding Liren. It ended in a draw after Ding chose to sacrifice a bishop and a rook to force a draw by three-fold repetition. Olympiad In September he joined his team-mates in Budapest for the Olympiad. This time India put out only one team - two years earlier it had been the host nation and so could enter additional teams. Gukesh was board one alongside his compatriots Erigaisi, Vidit, Praggnanandhaa and Harikrishna. They convincingly won the team gold medal with 10 wins and one draw. The Indian women's team also won gold, making for a huge celebration and a meeting with Indian prime minister Narendra Modi when they returned home. Just as he had done in the 2022 Olympiad, Gukesh took individual gold medal on the top board. His score of 9 points in 10 games came with a performance rating of 3056. His live rating went up to 2794.1, its highest ever. Interviewed afterwards, Gukesh referenced his crucial loss against Nodirbek Abdussatorov in the previous Olympiad in 2022 which he felt had cost his team the chance of winning gold: 'I had a personal debt to pay back. I think I could say last time we didnât win gold because of my mistake, and now I think I proved that that was just an accident and Iâm capable of more.' World Championship Gukesh's journey to the World Championship is almost complete. Game 1 of the match, Gukesh vs Ding, begins on November 25. The players will compete over 14 standard play games. Tie-breaks, if needed, take place on December 13. Good luck to both players! }  *


[Event "Masterful Moves: Gukesh"]
[White "10) Age 17-18. Road to the World Championship, 2024 "]
[Black "More about Gukesh: 9. Focus and ambition"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]

{ Focus and ambitionHow Gukesh talks in interviews reveals his drive, focus and ambition. âI want to become the youngest world chess champion,â he told ChessBase India in an interview at the Indian under-11 Championship in 2017. Two years later, âI want to become World Champion,â is what he told GibChess in an interview on YouTube. âFrom the start I was here to winâ â he explained to FIDE Chess in an interview on YouTube the day after he triumphed at the Candidates in 2024. When asked about potentially becoming the youngest world champion, he replied: âI probably said it a few years back when all these youngest records mattered to me but right now I just want to be the best, I donât care about being the youngest.â He followed that up by telling New In Chess magazine, âI really want to be the best player in the worldâ â a quote that was splashed across the publicationâs front page. On Gukesh's bookshelf at home, alongside the chess books are biographies and autobiographies of great sporting champions including Rafael Nadal, Andre Agassi and Abhinav Bhindra, India's first Olympic gold medallist. "With most of the champions, one of the key qualities is being focused, really wanting something and being disciplined," he told New In Chess in 2022. He explained how he applied that level of focus to his chess preparation: "During tournaments when there is an afternoon round, I don't see the pairings before I sleep, because I just want to get some good sleep. I used to see the pairings at night but then I realised at some point that it's getting in my head while I am sleeping." } 
1.--   *


