{ Speaking to New In Chess Gukesh's trainer Grzegorz Gajewski said Vidit had shown impressive preparation at the Candidates but 'we believed that in complex positions Gukesh should still have the upper hand. The first thing to deal with was the opening. We decided that it made sense to avoid a direct confrontation, so neutralising Vidit's preparation became a priority.' This explains why you will see Gukesh move both his rook's pawns by move number 5 in this game, avoiding some of the standard opening theory in the Italian game. } 
